WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.915 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.915 --> 00:00:02.415 align:middle line:90%


00:00:02.415 --> 00:00:03.847 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.847 --> 00:00:04.347 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.347 --> 00:00:05.796 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.796 --> 00:00:10.268 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.268 --> 00:00:12.060 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: All right,
let's get started.

00:00:12.060 --> 00:00:14.840 align:middle line:90%
Welcome back to 6.1200.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:18.110 align:middle line:84%
Today we're going to talk
about state machines, which

00:00:18.110 --> 00:00:23.820 align:middle line:84%
is a very cool tool for thinking
about processes over time.

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.962 align:middle line:84%
And because this is math for
computer science, in particular

00:00:26.962 --> 00:00:28.670 align:middle line:84%
we're thinking about
analyzing algorithms

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:30.330 align:middle line:90%
that do a bunch of steps.

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:34.260 align:middle line:84%
And the state of the
machine changes over time,

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:36.240 align:middle line:84%
like the state of
your memory changes.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:37.670 align:middle line:84%
And state machines
are a nice way

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:40.050 align:middle line:84%
to reason about
how it's changing.

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:43.190 align:middle line:84%
In particular, we'll talk about
an idea called invariance,

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:48.290 align:middle line:84%
which you use to prove
algorithms and programs correct,

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:49.890 align:middle line:90%
or you will in the future.

00:00:49.890 --> 00:00:52.100 align:middle line:84%
And so today we're
going to formalize that

00:00:52.100 --> 00:00:56.180 align:middle line:84%
into a kind of
induction, actually.

00:00:56.180 --> 00:00:59.060 align:middle line:84%
You haven't seen the
end of induction yet.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:02.640 align:middle line:84%
So let me tell you a little bit
about what state machines are.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:05.630 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll prove some
things and apply them

00:01:05.630 --> 00:01:08.680 align:middle line:84%
to analyzing puzzles
and other fun stuff.

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:13.040 align:middle line:90%


00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:19.130 align:middle line:84%
So a state machine is going
to consist of two things--

00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:22.623 align:middle line:90%
three things-- a set of states.

00:01:22.623 --> 00:01:25.760 align:middle line:90%


00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:28.920 align:middle line:84%
And the idea-- this is
just an arbitrary set.

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:30.980 align:middle line:84%
But the idea is that the
state of your machine

00:01:30.980 --> 00:01:33.620 align:middle line:84%
represents everything
that could possibly

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:37.700 align:middle line:84%
be in the machine, all
the information that's

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:40.970 align:middle line:90%
inside the machine.

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:46.123 align:middle line:84%
We're going to start in some
state, which we call q0.

00:01:46.123 --> 00:01:51.350 align:middle line:90%


00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:52.980 align:middle line:84%
That's going to be
an element of Q.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:56.226 align:middle line:84%
And then we are allowed
some transitions.

00:01:56.226 --> 00:02:09.389 align:middle line:90%


00:02:09.389 --> 00:02:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
write a transition

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:27.005 align:middle line:84%
as q arrow r for some q
and r that are states.

00:02:27.005 --> 00:02:31.320 align:middle line:90%


00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:36.510 align:middle line:84%
OK, let me draw you an example,
very simple example of a state

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.700 align:middle line:84%
machine so we have some idea
of what we're talking about.

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:41.703 align:middle line:84%
This is going to be
an infinite counter.

00:02:41.703 --> 00:02:45.450 align:middle line:90%


00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:48.120 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to draw
it visually first.

00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:50.585 align:middle line:84%
And then we can say what it
means with all these sets.

00:02:50.585 --> 00:02:54.510 align:middle line:90%


00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:55.627 align:middle line:90%
Just dot, dot, dot.

00:02:55.627 --> 00:02:56.585 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I'll do one more.

00:02:56.585 --> 00:03:01.800 align:middle line:90%


00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:04.030 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is a machine.

00:03:04.030 --> 00:03:07.510 align:middle line:84%
You can think of it as a single
register on your machine,

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:08.680 align:middle line:90%
single variable.

00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:10.030 align:middle line:90%
It starts at 0.

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:12.290 align:middle line:84%
This little notation
here means start state.

00:03:12.290 --> 00:03:14.940 align:middle line:90%


00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:17.017 align:middle line:84%
There's an arrow
coming from nowhere.

00:03:17.017 --> 00:03:18.100 align:middle line:90%
So that's where you start.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:19.990 align:middle line:90%
You start in state called 0.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:26.740 align:middle line:84%
So the set of states here
is 0, 1, 2, 3, and so on,

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:30.730 align:middle line:84%
in other words, the
natural numbers.

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:33.520 align:middle line:84%
And then when you're in state 0,
the only transition you can do,

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:35.982 align:middle line:84%
the only arrow that goes out
from there is from 0 to 1.

00:03:35.982 --> 00:03:38.190 align:middle line:84%
And once you're in state 1,
the only thing you can do

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:39.185 align:middle line:90%
is go from 1 to 2.

00:03:39.185 --> 00:03:40.810 align:middle line:84%
At some point, you
decide to increment.

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:41.950 align:middle line:90%
Then you go from 2 to 3.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:43.533 align:middle line:84%
At some point you
decide to increment,

00:03:43.533 --> 00:03:45.335 align:middle line:84%
and you go from 3
to 4, and so on.

00:03:45.335 --> 00:03:46.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is a very
simple state machine.

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:50.710 align:middle line:84%
It turns out it will be
interesting for certain reasons.

00:03:50.710 --> 00:03:53.220 align:middle line:84%
But in general,
you could imagine

00:03:53.220 --> 00:03:54.430 align:middle line:90%
having all sorts of arrows.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:58.450 align:middle line:84%
Maybe one has a transition
to 3, for example.

00:03:58.450 --> 00:04:00.430 align:middle line:84%
Or maybe 3 has a
transition to 1.

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:01.720 align:middle line:90%
All of these are possible.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:04.480 align:middle line:84%
You can have one state that
has many transitions out of it.

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:05.650 align:middle line:90%
You can go in loops.

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:08.250 align:middle line:84%
You can do all sorts
of crazy things.

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:11.890 align:middle line:84%
But let me finish precisely
specifying the counter.

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:17.640 align:middle line:84%
So we said here q0
equals the state 0.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:20.730 align:middle line:90%
And what are the transitions?

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:26.400 align:middle line:84%
Transitions are
all of the i to i

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:30.615 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 transitions where
i is a natural number.

00:04:30.615 --> 00:04:34.920 align:middle line:84%
You may recall this set-builder
notation from lecture 1,

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:38.670 align:middle line:84%
I think, where we write
an element on the left,

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:40.900 align:middle line:84%
and we write some
condition on the right.

00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:43.140 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea is
T is the set of all

00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:47.500 align:middle line:84%
of these transitions i
to i plus 1 for every i

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:50.746 align:middle line:90%
that's a natural number.

00:04:50.746 --> 00:04:51.933 align:middle line:90%
So that's an example.

00:04:51.933 --> 00:04:54.100 align:middle line:84%
But in general, we can have
all sorts of transitions

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:56.200 align:middle line:90%
from any state to any state.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:05:00.070 align:middle line:84%
But you're only allowed to make
the transitions that are in T.

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:10.806 align:middle line:84%
So let's formalize that
with the idea of execution.

00:05:10.806 --> 00:05:28.990 align:middle line:90%


00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:30.550 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be a
sequence of states

00:05:30.550 --> 00:05:35.380 align:middle line:84%
that you can reach by a
sequence of transitions.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:45.060 align:middle line:84%
So let's write it as q0, arrow,
q1, arrow, q2, and so on.

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:49.090 align:middle line:90%


00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:50.310 align:middle line:90%
Maybe up to qn.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:06:02.380 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:06.190 align:middle line:84%
And importantly, every
transition we make for all i,

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:11.640 align:middle line:84%
the qi to qi plus 1, should be
in T, not just any set of states

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:12.140 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:14.330 align:middle line:84%
We want to start in
q0, our start state.

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:17.980 align:middle line:84%
We want to then make a valid
transition from q0 to q1, then

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:21.280 align:middle line:84%
a valid transition from
q1 to q2, and so on.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.560 align:middle line:84%
So in this example, the
executions are very simple.

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:26.900 align:middle line:84%
In the regular counter
without the red lines,

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:29.360 align:middle line:84%
the executions are
just 0, 1, 2, 3.

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:30.250 align:middle line:90%
That's one execution.

00:06:30.250 --> 00:06:32.780 align:middle line:84%
0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, that's
another execution.

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:36.130 align:middle line:84%
There's an infinite execution,
which is 0 all the way out

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:38.560 align:middle line:90%
to infinity.

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:40.580 align:middle line:84%
That's why I put
this in parentheses.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:43.870 align:middle line:84%
Either it stops at some qn, or
it just-- or the dot, dot, dot

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:45.290 align:middle line:90%
continues off to infinity.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:47.300 align:middle line:84%
So we're trying to
simultaneously define

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:49.680 align:middle line:84%
finite executions,
where you stop at qn,

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:53.780 align:middle line:84%
and infinite executions,
where you go forever.

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:56.700 align:middle line:84%
When you write an algorithm
or a piece of code,

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.010 align:middle line:84%
you usually don't want
your program to go forever.

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:02.780 align:middle line:84%
And so distinguishing between
infinite and finite executions

00:07:02.780 --> 00:07:04.280 align:middle line:84%
is one of the goals
of this lecture.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:05.990 align:middle line:90%
That will come at the end.

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:09.020 align:middle line:84%
The other goal is to
show that your program is

00:07:09.020 --> 00:07:12.510 align:middle line:84%
correct in a certain sense,
that in any execution,

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:14.870 align:middle line:84%
it does the things
that you want it to do.

00:07:14.870 --> 00:07:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we're going
to formalize in a moment.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:23.000 align:middle line:84%
But let me first talk
about reachable states,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:24.196 align:middle line:90%
the idea of reachability.

00:07:24.196 --> 00:07:42.590 align:middle line:90%


00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:44.600 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to call
a state r reachable

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:50.480 align:middle line:84%
if there is an execution that
starts at the start state q0

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:52.933 align:middle line:90%
and ends at r.

00:07:52.933 --> 00:07:55.530 align:middle line:90%


00:07:55.530 --> 00:07:59.070 align:middle line:84%
So in the counter example,
every state can be reached.

00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:03.410 align:middle line:84%
If I pick a state i, I can
go 0, 1, 2, 3, up to i.

00:08:03.410 --> 00:08:08.540 align:middle line:84%
But if I drew some other
circle over here, like "bad,"

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:12.440 align:middle line:84%
with no arrows coming into
it, you can't reach "bad."

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So usually we're only interested
in the reachable states

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:20.800 align:middle line:84%
because you can't
get anywhere else.

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:25.100 align:middle line:90%


00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:26.910 align:middle line:84%
I feel like I should
make a Reacher joke,

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:28.570 align:middle line:90%
but I can't think of one.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:36.110 align:middle line:90%


00:08:36.110 --> 00:08:40.970 align:middle line:84%
I think, at this point, I want
to talk about a more interesting

00:08:40.970 --> 00:08:41.940 align:middle line:90%
example.

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:49.855 align:middle line:84%
And then we will come
back to the theory.

00:08:49.855 --> 00:08:59.840 align:middle line:90%


00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:04.010 align:middle line:84%
So the interesting
example is this.

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:05.430 align:middle line:90%
It's called the 8 puzzle.

00:09:05.430 --> 00:09:11.130 align:middle line:84%
You have a 3-by-3 grid with one
hole and 1-by-1 pieces in it.

00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:13.700 align:middle line:90%
And you can slide them around.

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:15.600 align:middle line:90%
And so this is the solved state.

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.310 align:middle line:90%
Your goal is to get here.

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:21.050 align:middle line:84%
But you start in
some random state.

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And you want to move the
pieces around to get there.

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:32.820 align:middle line:84%
So what we'd like to do is
capture how to solve this puzzle

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.310 align:middle line:84%
or actually, maybe
more interestingly,

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:36.810 align:middle line:90%
is when it's solvable.

00:09:36.810 --> 00:09:42.660 align:middle line:84%
So here, for example, I'm almost
solved 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 5, 7, 8.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:45.740 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to get it to
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

00:09:45.740 --> 00:09:48.810 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that
puzzle is not solvable.

00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:53.000 align:middle line:84%
I claim it's impossible to
get from here to the goal.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.155 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk
about the 8 puzzle.

00:09:56.155 --> 00:10:04.940 align:middle line:90%


00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.140 align:middle line:90%
So I have some examples here.

00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:13.580 align:middle line:90%
1, 3, 4, 2, 5, 7, 8, 6.

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:17.270 align:middle line:90%


00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:21.816 align:middle line:90%
Going to 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

00:10:21.816 --> 00:10:25.730 align:middle line:90%


00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:35.080 align:middle line:84%
Or this one-- 1, 2,
3, 4, 6, 5, 7, 8.

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:39.800 align:middle line:90%


00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:41.050 align:middle line:90%
Hopefully the rules are clear.

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:44.220 align:middle line:84%
We'll formalize
them in a second.

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:47.280 align:middle line:84%
I claim it is possible to
go from this arrangement

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:48.990 align:middle line:90%
to this arrangement.

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:50.230 align:middle line:90%
It's actually quite easy.

00:10:50.230 --> 00:10:51.400 align:middle line:90%
You move the 3 over.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:52.450 align:middle line:90%
You move the 2 up.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:53.470 align:middle line:90%
You move the 5 over.

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:55.390 align:middle line:90%
You move the 6 up.

00:10:55.390 --> 00:10:57.510 align:middle line:90%
So this is possible.

00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:01.920 align:middle line:90%
I claim this one is impossible.

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:06.700 align:middle line:84%
And one of the goals-- our first
goal really is to prove that,

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.370 align:middle line:84%
that you cannot swap the
5 and the 6 by themselves.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:13.820 align:middle line:84%
We're going to build
up tools to do that.

00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:20.170 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:22.270 align:middle line:84%
So the counter was a very
simple state machine.

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:24.020 align:middle line:84%
Let me now define a
more interesting state

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:25.670 align:middle line:90%
machine, which is the 8 puzzle.

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:39.390 align:middle line:90%


00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:42.720 align:middle line:84%
Remember, the set of
states q is supposed

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:47.490 align:middle line:84%
to encapsulate everything
about the puzzle or your system

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:48.990 align:middle line:90%
or whatever.

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:51.990 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to be all
the different arrangements

00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:57.870 align:middle line:84%
of the eight pieces, plus
a blank, in a 3-by-3 grid.

00:11:57.870 --> 00:12:00.760 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just going to
write that in words.

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:12.840 align:middle line:84%
All possible
arrangements of eight--

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:22.770 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to call them of 1,
2, 3, up to 8, and the blank,

00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:25.590 align:middle line:90%
in a 3-by-3.

00:12:25.590 --> 00:12:27.240 align:middle line:84%
In later parts of
the class, we'll

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:29.680 align:middle line:84%
be able to count how many
of these things there are.

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:30.670 align:middle line:90%
It's nine factorial.

00:12:30.670 --> 00:12:33.190 align:middle line:84%
But we don't really care how
many there are right now.

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:35.190 align:middle line:84%
We just want to think
about this as a set of all

00:12:35.190 --> 00:12:39.150 align:middle line:84%
the possible states
of this board.

00:12:39.150 --> 00:12:44.230 align:middle line:84%
Our start state, well, that's
either this one or this one,

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:47.070 align:middle line:84%
depending on where
we want to start.

00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:52.200 align:middle line:84%
We're also going to define
a final state, q sub f.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:58.220 align:middle line:84%
And that is sorted
by reading order.

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:03.180 align:middle line:90%


00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:05.490 align:middle line:90%
So this is q sub f.

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:07.140 align:middle line:90%
Reading order-- like in English.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:09.210 align:middle line:84%
You read the top row,
second row, third row,

00:13:09.210 --> 00:13:10.980 align:middle line:90%
with the x at the end.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.410 align:middle line:84%
That's always our
goal in this puzzle.

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:15.450 align:middle line:90%
That's our definition.

00:13:15.450 --> 00:13:19.726 align:middle line:84%
And then, what about
the transitions?

00:13:19.726 --> 00:13:23.280 align:middle line:90%


00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:26.520 align:middle line:84%
Transitions are going
to look like some q

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.590 align:middle line:90%
to r for two states q and r.

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:35.440 align:middle line:84%
And it's when you can get from
q to r by making one slide.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:37.660 align:middle line:84%
I'm just going to
write that in words--

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:42.940 align:middle line:84%
can get from state
q, that 3-by-3 grid,

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:47.096 align:middle line:84%
to state r in one
slide, meaning--

00:13:47.096 --> 00:13:49.630 align:middle line:90%


00:13:49.630 --> 00:13:52.750 align:middle line:84%
meaning you exchange
the blank, the x,

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:54.950 align:middle line:84%
with one of its
neighboring cells.

00:13:54.950 --> 00:14:02.200 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, there is at
most four different transitions

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:03.390 align:middle line:90%
from any state.

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:06.910 align:middle line:90%


00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:10.100 align:middle line:84%
You could move the thing above
the blank into the blank.

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:13.190 align:middle line:84%
You can move the left, right, or
below the blank into the blank.

00:14:13.190 --> 00:14:16.510 align:middle line:84%
But if it's on the boundary,
you have fewer than four moves.

00:14:16.510 --> 00:14:18.260 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully now I've
said it enough times

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.718 align:middle line:84%
the rules are clear if you
haven't played this game before.

00:14:20.718 --> 00:14:24.700 align:middle line:84%
15 puzzle is much more common,
but 8 puzzle is a little easier

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:25.700 align:middle line:90%
to think about--

00:14:25.700 --> 00:14:27.860 align:middle line:84%
smaller pictures,
easier to draw,

00:14:27.860 --> 00:14:31.870 align:middle line:84%
and I can actually solve it in
a reasonable amount of time.

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:41.140 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is a claim
that we want to prove.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:45.040 align:middle line:84%
You cannot get from this
state, with 5 and 6 flipped,

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:46.250 align:middle line:90%
into this state.

00:14:46.250 --> 00:14:50.240 align:middle line:84%
And so now we're going to build
some technology to do that.

00:14:50.240 --> 00:14:52.180 align:middle line:90%
And that technology is a--

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:55.990 align:middle line:84%
first part of it is
called a state predicate.

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:59.713 align:middle line:90%
So we've seen predicates before.

00:14:59.713 --> 00:15:04.840 align:middle line:90%


00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:06.765 align:middle line:90%
Predicate is just a--

00:15:06.765 --> 00:15:13.300 align:middle line:90%


00:15:13.300 --> 00:15:19.450 align:middle line:84%
a proposition that
depends on some variable.

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:22.720 align:middle line:84%
And here, the
variable is a state.

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:25.180 align:middle line:84%
So P of q is either
true or false

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:28.160 align:middle line:84%
depending on which state
you are looking at.

00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:30.918 align:middle line:84%
You can also think of this,
if you're comfortable with

00:15:30.918 --> 00:15:32.960 align:middle line:84%
functions-- we'll talk
more about functions later

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:33.870 align:middle line:90%
in the class--

00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:41.930 align:middle line:84%
this is a function from q to
the Booleans true or false.

00:15:41.930 --> 00:15:44.592 align:middle line:84%
It's an equivalent way to
think about it, whatever

00:15:44.592 --> 00:15:45.800 align:middle line:90%
you're more comfortable with.

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:50.480 align:middle line:84%
For every state, this predicate
assigns true or false.

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:56.000 align:middle line:84%
Now we're going to define
two types of predicates that

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.390 align:middle line:90%
are particularly interesting.

00:15:59.390 --> 00:16:03.440 align:middle line:84%
A predicate is
preserved if whenever

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:11.620 align:middle line:84%
there's a transition from q
to r, P of q implies P of r.

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:14.180 align:middle line:90%


00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:15.420 align:middle line:90%
What does that mean?

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:19.550 align:middle line:84%
It means that if I start in
some state where P is true

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:23.510 align:middle line:84%
and I do a transition,
then P remains true.

00:16:23.510 --> 00:16:29.450 align:middle line:84%
So the truth of p is
preserved along transitions.

00:16:29.450 --> 00:16:31.230 align:middle line:84%
We'll make this
concrete in a second.

00:16:31.230 --> 00:16:35.690 align:middle line:84%
Second important notion
is called an invariant,

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:42.470 align:middle line:84%
or invariant state
predicate, if P of q

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:47.575 align:middle line:84%
is true for all
reachable states q.

00:16:47.575 --> 00:16:53.690 align:middle line:90%


00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:56.060 align:middle line:84%
Crucially, in this
definition, we're

00:16:56.060 --> 00:17:00.050 align:middle line:84%
only interested in
the reachable states.

00:17:00.050 --> 00:17:02.040 align:middle line:84%
That's kind of important
for the 8 puzzle

00:17:02.040 --> 00:17:04.582 align:middle line:84%
because we claim some
states are unreachable.

00:17:04.582 --> 00:17:07.290 align:middle line:84%
Like, if I start here, the claim
is that this one is unreachable.

00:17:07.290 --> 00:17:11.060 align:middle line:84%
That's what we'd like
to prove actually.

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:12.463 align:middle line:90%
So this seems useful.

00:17:12.463 --> 00:17:15.050 align:middle line:90%


00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:24.630 align:middle line:84%
In particular-- let's
write this fun fact--

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:28.970 align:middle line:84%
if P of q is
invariant, meaning it's

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:42.440 align:middle line:84%
true in all reachable states,
and P of q is false for,

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:48.766 align:middle line:84%
maybe I'll write P of r
here, then r is unreachable.

00:17:48.766 --> 00:17:54.090 align:middle line:90%


00:17:54.090 --> 00:17:57.120 align:middle line:84%
That's pretty much by definition
and maybe the contrapositive.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:59.810 align:middle line:84%
This is saying invariant means
that for all reachable states,

00:17:59.810 --> 00:18:01.320 align:middle line:90%
P of q must be true.

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:04.890 align:middle line:84%
So if I can find a particular
state r where P is false,

00:18:04.890 --> 00:18:06.740 align:middle line:90%
that means you cannot reach it.

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:08.250 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we'd like to show.

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:12.290 align:middle line:84%
We'd like to show this state
is unreachable from this one.

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:16.020 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we can use these
state predicates to do that,

00:18:16.020 --> 00:18:17.080 align:middle line:90%
and indeed we can.

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:22.580 align:middle line:90%


00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:24.520 align:middle line:90%
Let me tell you another tool.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:27.680 align:middle line:90%


00:18:27.680 --> 00:18:33.410 align:middle line:84%
How do we prove that a state
predicate is invariant?

00:18:33.410 --> 00:18:35.720 align:middle line:84%
This seems a little bit
tricky because this is talking

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:36.930 align:middle line:90%
about all reachable states.

00:18:36.930 --> 00:18:38.700 align:middle line:90%
Reachable states is huge.

00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:40.220 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:42.570 align:middle line:84%
Preserved seems
relatively easy to prove.

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:44.690 align:middle line:84%
This is just saying,
for each transition,

00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:46.440 align:middle line:90%
something implies something.

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:49.670 align:middle line:84%
So I'd like to
prove preservedness.

00:18:49.670 --> 00:18:52.580 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like to use
that to get invariant.

00:18:52.580 --> 00:18:55.500 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to do
that using induction,

00:18:55.500 --> 00:18:57.680 align:middle line:84%
but a particular
form of induction

00:18:57.680 --> 00:18:59.416 align:middle line:90%
called the invariant principle.

00:18:59.416 --> 00:19:09.740 align:middle line:90%


00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:28.890 align:middle line:84%
So this is for a state predicate
P of q, if P of q0 is true

00:19:28.890 --> 00:19:36.476 align:middle line:90%
and P of q is invariant--

00:19:36.476 --> 00:19:39.720 align:middle line:90%


00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:42.836 align:middle line:90%
get it right; preserved--

00:19:42.836 --> 00:19:46.890 align:middle line:90%


00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:52.736 align:middle line:90%
then P of q is invariant.

00:19:52.736 --> 00:19:57.360 align:middle line:90%


00:19:57.360 --> 00:19:59.620 align:middle line:90%
This is what I said I wanted.

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:03.070 align:middle line:84%
On the one hand, invariance
seemed hard to argue.

00:20:03.070 --> 00:20:04.800 align:middle line:90%
Preserved seemed easy to argue.

00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:07.238 align:middle line:84%
And this is the theorem that
connects them in the way

00:20:07.238 --> 00:20:07.780 align:middle line:90%
that we want.

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:09.510 align:middle line:84%
It says, if you
can prove preserved

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:12.760 align:middle line:84%
and you can prove that P is
true in the very initial state,

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:14.805 align:middle line:90%
then it must be invariant.

00:20:14.805 --> 00:20:16.180 align:middle line:84%
I think this is
intuitive, right?

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:18.450 align:middle line:84%
If you start true
and preserve says,

00:20:18.450 --> 00:20:20.572 align:middle line:84%
every time you do a
transition, you stay true,

00:20:20.572 --> 00:20:23.030 align:middle line:84%
then you're always going to be
true in any reachable state,

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:23.910 align:middle line:90%
anywhere you can get.

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:27.950 align:middle line:90%


00:20:27.950 --> 00:20:32.360 align:middle line:84%
In fact, this is
induction in another form.

00:20:32.360 --> 00:20:36.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you recall
in the past, which

00:20:36.850 --> 00:20:41.050 align:middle line:84%
I happen to have right
here, induction, we have--

00:20:41.050 --> 00:20:44.890 align:middle line:84%
regular induction
says for predicate P

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:49.570 align:middle line:84%
of n over natural numbers
instead of states, if P of 0

00:20:49.570 --> 00:20:51.760 align:middle line:84%
is true, and for every
natural number P of n

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:54.910 align:middle line:84%
implies P of n plus
1 is true, then

00:20:54.910 --> 00:20:58.060 align:middle line:84%
for every natural
number P of n is true.

00:20:58.060 --> 00:21:00.560 align:middle line:90%
This is saying the same thing.

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:02.380 align:middle line:84%
Actually, it's
exactly the same thing

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:06.963 align:middle line:84%
if you apply this invariant
principle to this counter.

00:21:06.963 --> 00:21:10.870 align:middle line:90%


00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:14.210 align:middle line:84%
In the counter, the states
are the natural numbers.

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:18.630 align:middle line:84%
And the transitions are exactly
going from i to i plus 1.

00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:21.630 align:middle line:84%
So the invariant principle
is actually a generalization

00:21:21.630 --> 00:21:24.150 align:middle line:90%
of the induction axiom.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:26.400 align:middle line:84%
The special case
here, where we plug

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:28.210 align:middle line:84%
in the counter as
the state machine,

00:21:28.210 --> 00:21:30.190 align:middle line:84%
this is true for
all state machines.

00:21:30.190 --> 00:21:32.530 align:middle line:84%
And if we plug in the counter
for our state machine,

00:21:32.530 --> 00:21:36.930 align:middle line:84%
we get exactly the
induction axiom.

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:39.490 align:middle line:84%
This is our base
case in some sense.

00:21:39.490 --> 00:21:42.670 align:middle line:84%
We prove that P is true
in the initial state.

00:21:42.670 --> 00:21:44.080 align:middle line:90%
This is our induction step.

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:46.590 align:middle line:84%
It says that if we start
at q and we transition

00:21:46.590 --> 00:21:50.910 align:middle line:84%
to some other r that's
reachable via transition,

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:54.390 align:middle line:84%
and in the particular
case of a counter that

00:21:54.390 --> 00:21:58.830 align:middle line:84%
is going from q to q plus
1, then we get that P of q

00:21:58.830 --> 00:22:00.250 align:middle line:84%
is true for all
reachable states.

00:22:00.250 --> 00:22:03.060 align:middle line:84%
And in the counter,
everything is reachable.

00:22:03.060 --> 00:22:08.970 align:middle line:84%
So invariant principle
implies induction axiom.

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:12.780 align:middle line:84%
Conversely, we can prove
the invariant principle

00:22:12.780 --> 00:22:14.080 align:middle line:90%
using induction.

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:17.490 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's useful
to see that proof.

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:23.380 align:middle line:90%


00:22:23.380 --> 00:22:30.336 align:middle line:84%
So let's prove the invariant
principle by induction.

00:22:30.336 --> 00:22:34.090 align:middle line:90%


00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:36.710 align:middle line:84%
So it's not so
obvious how exactly.

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:39.670 align:middle line:84%
But the idea is to specify
a particular induction

00:22:39.670 --> 00:23:03.970 align:middle line:84%
hypothesis, which is, for all
length n executions, P of qn

00:23:03.970 --> 00:23:06.470 align:middle line:90%
is true.

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:07.845 align:middle line:84%
There should be
a colon out here.

00:23:07.845 --> 00:23:10.840 align:middle line:90%


00:23:10.840 --> 00:23:12.758 align:middle line:84%
I think it's intuitive
that this is enough.

00:23:12.758 --> 00:23:14.300 align:middle line:84%
But we'll justify
why this is enough.

00:23:14.300 --> 00:23:17.060 align:middle line:84%
The idea is if you have
some state that's reachable,

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:20.900 align:middle line:84%
it's reachable by some finite
execution of some length.

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:23.740 align:middle line:84%
And we're going
to prove for all n

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:27.770 align:middle line:84%
that all length n
executions P of qn is true.

00:23:27.770 --> 00:23:31.660 align:middle line:84%
And by inducting over
length, we essentially

00:23:31.660 --> 00:23:35.840 align:middle line:84%
start with short executions and
then make them gradually longer.

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:37.430 align:middle line:84%
And that makes
this easy to prove.

00:23:37.430 --> 00:23:45.730 align:middle line:84%
So let's do a base
case, IH of 0.

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:48.410 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's all
length 0 executions.

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:50.526 align:middle line:84%
There's only one
length 0 execution.

00:23:50.526 --> 00:23:56.590 align:middle line:90%


00:23:56.590 --> 00:23:58.700 align:middle line:90%
That is just q0.

00:23:58.700 --> 00:24:00.470 align:middle line:84%
You start at q0,
and you stay there.

00:24:00.470 --> 00:24:02.710 align:middle line:90%
That's length 0.

00:24:02.710 --> 00:24:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And we claim that P of q0-- q0
is clearly a reachable state.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:10.820 align:middle line:84%
You get there via
length 0 execution.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:13.720 align:middle line:90%
Why is it true?

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:15.160 align:middle line:90%
This.

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:16.320 align:middle line:90%
It's what we assumed.

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:19.720 align:middle line:90%


00:24:19.720 --> 00:24:23.470 align:middle line:90%
OK, so by 1.

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:26.470 align:middle line:90%
So that's the base case.

00:24:26.470 --> 00:24:29.200 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the more interesting
one is the induction step.

00:24:29.200 --> 00:24:32.560 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to assume--

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:33.860 align:middle line:90%
we get to choose.

00:24:33.860 --> 00:24:35.830 align:middle line:84%
We could follow this
plan, assume P of n

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:37.520 align:middle line:90%
And prove P of n plus 1.

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:42.010 align:middle line:84%
I find it slightly more
intuitive to assume P of n--

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:46.450 align:middle line:84%
or sorry, instead of P, it's IH
here for induction hypothesis--

00:24:46.450 --> 00:24:49.360 align:middle line:90%
IH of n minus 1.

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:53.310 align:middle line:84%
And we're going
to prove IH of n.

00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:55.870 align:middle line:90%


00:24:55.870 --> 00:24:58.220 align:middle line:84%
What does it mean
to prove IH of n?

00:24:58.220 --> 00:25:02.350 align:middle line:84%
It says, well, for all length
n executions, P of qn is true.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:04.520 align:middle line:90%
So how do we prove it for all?

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:09.050 align:middle line:84%
We just take an arbitrary
thing in the quantifier.

00:25:09.050 --> 00:25:17.876 align:middle line:84%
So take any-- consider
any length and execution.

00:25:17.876 --> 00:25:21.650 align:middle line:90%


00:25:21.650 --> 00:25:24.360 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to prove
the property we want,

00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:26.280 align:middle line:90%
which is P of qn.

00:25:26.280 --> 00:25:31.910 align:middle line:84%
So let me give some
notation for that execution.

00:25:31.910 --> 00:25:44.930 align:middle line:84%
Any length n execution
q0, q1, qn minus 1, qn.

00:25:44.930 --> 00:25:51.140 align:middle line:84%
And what we want to
show is that P of qn.

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:52.170 align:middle line:90%
That's our goal right.

00:25:52.170 --> 00:25:55.770 align:middle line:84%
It says, for all length n
executions, P of qn is true.

00:25:55.770 --> 00:25:57.390 align:middle line:84%
So we take an
arbitrary execution.

00:25:57.390 --> 00:26:01.940 align:middle line:84%
If we can prove P of qn
is true, then we're done.

00:26:01.940 --> 00:26:04.440 align:middle line:84%
Well, somehow we want
to use induction here.

00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:08.010 align:middle line:84%
We've assumed the induction
hypothesis for size n minus 1.

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:11.790 align:middle line:84%
Can you see a length
n-minus-1 execution here

00:26:11.790 --> 00:26:13.110 align:middle line:90%
that might be interesting?

00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:18.600 align:middle line:90%


00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:19.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:20.400 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: q1 to qn.

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:22.350 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: q1 to qn.

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:23.960 align:middle line:90%
That's a good idea.

00:26:23.960 --> 00:26:26.900 align:middle line:90%
Does that work?

00:26:26.900 --> 00:26:29.510 align:middle line:90%
Is that an execution?

00:26:29.510 --> 00:26:32.570 align:middle line:90%
Let's go back and check.

00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:37.760 align:middle line:84%
Execution of a state
machine is an infinite

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:42.860 align:middle line:84%
or a finite sequence starting
with q0 and maybe ending.

00:26:42.860 --> 00:26:45.020 align:middle line:90%
But it needs to start with q0.

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:47.400 align:middle line:84%
So there's two
natural choices here.

00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:49.830 align:middle line:84%
One would be starting
at q1 and going to qn.

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:51.840 align:middle line:90%
But q1 might not equal q0.

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:53.490 align:middle line:84%
So that might not be
a valid execution.

00:26:53.490 --> 00:26:55.640 align:middle line:84%
So we wouldn't be able to
apply induction to that.

00:26:55.640 --> 00:27:00.660 align:middle line:84%
The other obvious choice
is q0 to qn minus 1.

00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:03.140 align:middle line:84%
That is a valid
execution of length 1

00:27:03.140 --> 00:27:07.370 align:middle line:84%
smaller, length n minus 1,
because it starts with q0.

00:27:07.370 --> 00:27:08.790 align:middle line:90%
A lot of terms here.

00:27:08.790 --> 00:27:10.680 align:middle line:90%
So it's easy to lose track.

00:27:10.680 --> 00:27:14.960 align:middle line:84%
But eventually, they
will become comfortable.

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:22.670 align:middle line:84%
So by induction
hypothesis of n minus 1,

00:27:22.670 --> 00:27:26.520 align:middle line:84%
if we apply it to this
execution of length n minus 1,

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:30.880 align:middle line:84%
we learn that P of
q n minus 1 is true.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:34.040 align:middle line:90%


00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:36.270 align:middle line:84%
That's what the induction
hypothesis says.

00:27:36.270 --> 00:27:39.920 align:middle line:84%
The last state in your
execution is true.

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:41.970 align:middle line:84%
So now we know P
of this is true.

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.010 align:middle line:84%
We just need to prove
P of this is true.

00:27:44.010 --> 00:27:45.000 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:49.772 align:middle line:90%
Because property 2--

00:27:49.772 --> 00:27:53.600 align:middle line:84%
P of q is preserved, which
we can unroll over here.

00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:56.090 align:middle line:84%
Says, for every transition,
in particular the one

00:27:56.090 --> 00:28:01.130 align:middle line:84%
from qn minus 1 to qn, P of
q minus 1 implies P of qn.

00:28:01.130 --> 00:28:04.440 align:middle line:90%


00:28:04.440 --> 00:28:17.010 align:middle line:84%
So by 2, P of q n
minus 1 implies P of qn

00:28:17.010 --> 00:28:25.830 align:middle line:84%
because this is a
transition in T. So P of qn.

00:28:25.830 --> 00:28:29.160 align:middle line:84%
So that's the end of
the induction step.

00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:42.810 align:middle line:84%
So by induction, we get, for all
n, induction hypothesis of n.

00:28:42.810 --> 00:28:46.380 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is
that this implies

00:28:46.380 --> 00:28:56.880 align:middle line:84%
P of q for all
reachable states q

00:28:56.880 --> 00:28:59.400 align:middle line:84%
because if you have
a reachable state q,

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:03.030 align:middle line:84%
there's, by definition, a
reachable way over on the left.

00:29:03.030 --> 00:29:06.910 align:middle line:84%
There's some execution that gets
there, and it has some length.

00:29:06.910 --> 00:29:10.980 align:middle line:84%
And so IH of that length
gives you what you want.

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:13.330 align:middle line:84%
So that's how we prove
the invariant principle.

00:29:13.330 --> 00:29:14.920 align:middle line:90%
It's a pretty intuitive notion.

00:29:14.920 --> 00:29:18.780 align:middle line:84%
But may be nice to see yet
another example of an induction

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:21.180 align:middle line:90%
proof.

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:23.010 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:26.970 align:middle line:90%
So how do we use this?

00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:29.960 align:middle line:90%
Let's go over here.

00:29:29.960 --> 00:29:33.360 align:middle line:90%


00:29:33.360 --> 00:29:41.160 align:middle line:84%
Here is a template for
proving a theorem, which

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:46.780 align:middle line:90%
is P of q is invariant.

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:49.440 align:middle line:84%
This is the thing I keep
saying is hard to prove.

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:52.842 align:middle line:84%
Or by the definition,
it seems hard to prove.

00:29:52.842 --> 00:29:54.300 align:middle line:84%
But using this
invariant principle,

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:55.390 align:middle line:90%
it's going to be easy.

00:29:55.390 --> 00:29:59.250 align:middle line:84%
Here's what a general
proof will look like.

00:29:59.250 --> 00:30:03.450 align:middle line:84%
We can say, proof by
invariant principle.

00:30:03.450 --> 00:30:05.410 align:middle line:84%
For the invariant
principle to apply,

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:08.580 align:middle line:90%
we need to prove two things--

00:30:08.580 --> 00:30:11.910 align:middle line:90%
number 1 and number 2.

00:30:11.910 --> 00:30:19.350 align:middle line:84%
So number one is prove
that P of q0 is true.

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:23.370 align:middle line:84%
And in a template, we just say
because reasons which we don't

00:30:23.370 --> 00:30:26.040 align:middle line:90%
know, or we have to fill in.

00:30:26.040 --> 00:30:34.593 align:middle line:84%
And the second thing is
that P of q is preserved.

00:30:34.593 --> 00:30:36.010 align:middle line:84%
That's the more
interesting thing.

00:30:36.010 --> 00:30:39.450 align:middle line:84%
And for this, we need to unroll
the definition of "preserved."

00:30:39.450 --> 00:30:45.570 align:middle line:84%
Says for all q, all transitions
q to r, P of q implies q of r.

00:30:45.570 --> 00:30:49.150 align:middle line:90%
So how do we prove that?

00:30:49.150 --> 00:31:01.840 align:middle line:84%
We just take any
transition in t, q to r.

00:31:01.840 --> 00:31:06.992 align:middle line:84%
And because it's an implication,
we can assume the left-hand--

00:31:06.992 --> 00:31:08.450 align:middle line:84%
if we want to prove
an implication,

00:31:08.450 --> 00:31:09.740 align:middle line:90%
we can assume the left part--

00:31:09.740 --> 00:31:12.550 align:middle line:84%
this is the direct proof--
and prove the right part.

00:31:12.550 --> 00:31:19.090 align:middle line:90%
So we can assume P of q is true.

00:31:19.090 --> 00:31:24.820 align:middle line:84%
And then what we need to do
is show that P of r is true.

00:31:24.820 --> 00:31:30.550 align:middle line:84%
That's the interesting step,
which we need to fill in.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:33.670 align:middle line:84%
But this is the template
we're going to now use

00:31:33.670 --> 00:31:36.520 align:middle line:90%
to analyze the 8 puzzle.

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:39.290 align:middle line:84%
Of course, I haven't defined
what predicate we're analyzing.

00:31:39.290 --> 00:31:41.470 align:middle line:90%
That's the next step.

00:31:41.470 --> 00:31:43.780 align:middle line:84%
But once we have
a predicate, we'll

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:45.280 align:middle line:84%
be able to prove
that it's invariant

00:31:45.280 --> 00:31:47.800 align:middle line:90%
using this simple structure.

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:48.790 align:middle line:90%
Just check it.

00:31:48.790 --> 00:31:50.240 align:middle line:90%
Check that it's initially true.

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:52.120 align:middle line:84%
And check that if you start
from something that's true

00:31:52.120 --> 00:31:54.328 align:middle line:84%
and you take a transition
out of it, it's still true.

00:31:54.328 --> 00:31:56.855 align:middle line:90%


00:31:56.855 --> 00:31:57.355 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:31:57.355 --> 00:32:10.150 align:middle line:90%


00:32:10.150 --> 00:32:16.840 align:middle line:84%
So let me define a
predicate for the 8 puzzle.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:19.205 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I want it closer to
these examples, actually.

00:32:19.205 --> 00:32:22.210 align:middle line:90%


00:32:22.210 --> 00:32:27.665 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let's go here.

00:32:27.665 --> 00:32:29.790 align:middle line:84%
I think you know the
definition of a state machine.

00:32:29.790 --> 00:32:48.130 align:middle line:90%


00:32:48.130 --> 00:32:51.830 align:middle line:84%
OK, so for this
8-puzzle state machine,

00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:56.780 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to define a bit
of a bizarre predicate.

00:32:56.780 --> 00:33:20.320 align:middle line:90%


00:33:20.320 --> 00:33:28.813 align:middle line:84%
So first, I'm going to define
the notion of an inverted pair.

00:33:28.813 --> 00:34:09.710 align:middle line:90%


00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:13.670 align:middle line:84%
This is going to depend
on what state we're in.

00:34:13.670 --> 00:34:20.780 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at inverted
pairs in this example

00:34:20.780 --> 00:34:23.780 align:middle line:90%
and use three examples.

00:34:23.780 --> 00:34:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So an inverted pair
is two numbers, so not

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:30.480 align:middle line:84%
the blank but two
numbers between 1 and 8.

00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:32.610 align:middle line:90%
And I want i less than j.

00:34:32.610 --> 00:34:37.820 align:middle line:84%
And yet I want j to appear
before i in the reading order.

00:34:37.820 --> 00:34:43.250 align:middle line:90%
So for example-- my red chalk--

00:34:43.250 --> 00:34:49.320 align:middle line:84%
in this picture, this
state, 2 and 4 are inverted.

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:55.010 align:middle line:84%
In reading order, 4 comes before
2, yet 4 is greater than 2.

00:34:55.010 --> 00:34:55.730 align:middle line:90%
Any others?

00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:59.242 align:middle line:90%


00:34:59.242 --> 00:35:03.260 align:middle line:90%
8 and 6 are inverted.

00:35:03.260 --> 00:35:05.910 align:middle line:90%
6 and 7 are inverted.

00:35:05.910 --> 00:35:07.040 align:middle line:90%
7 is bigger than 6.

00:35:07.040 --> 00:35:08.010 align:middle line:90%
8 is bigger than 6.

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:11.250 align:middle line:84%
But they come earlier than
6 in the reading order.

00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:13.961 align:middle line:90%
I think there's one more.

00:35:13.961 --> 00:35:14.790 align:middle line:90%
3 and--

00:35:14.790 --> 00:35:15.290 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: 2.

00:35:15.290 --> 00:35:16.460 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: 2.

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:17.190 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:35:17.190 --> 00:35:19.773 align:middle line:84%
That's one's a little trickier
because it's on different rows.

00:35:19.773 --> 00:35:21.990 align:middle line:84%
But in reading order,
3 comes before 2,

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:23.580 align:middle line:90%
and yet 3 is greater than 2.

00:35:23.580 --> 00:35:28.820 align:middle line:84%
So there are four inverted
pairs in this example.

00:35:28.820 --> 00:35:32.840 align:middle line:84%
How many inverted pairs
are there in this example?

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:34.910 align:middle line:90%
Zero.

00:35:34.910 --> 00:35:37.550 align:middle line:90%
Zero inverted pairs.

00:35:37.550 --> 00:35:38.605 align:middle line:90%
How about this one?

00:35:38.605 --> 00:35:42.950 align:middle line:90%


00:35:42.950 --> 00:35:45.043 align:middle line:90%
One, yeah.

00:35:45.043 --> 00:35:46.710 align:middle line:84%
I thought you were
holding up your hand.

00:35:46.710 --> 00:35:48.085 align:middle line:84%
But you're holding
up one finger.

00:35:48.085 --> 00:35:48.780 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:49.280 align:middle line:90%


00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:50.850 align:middle line:90%
6 comes after 5.

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:52.890 align:middle line:84%
That was the only
thing out of order.

00:35:52.890 --> 00:35:55.550 align:middle line:90%
That's what we started out with.

00:35:55.550 --> 00:35:57.630 align:middle line:84%
Where do you come
up with this idea?

00:35:57.630 --> 00:35:59.280 align:middle line:90%
It just is fundamental.

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:02.400 align:middle line:84%
You're supposed to
magically invent it.

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:04.350 align:middle line:84%
But if you fool around
with the puzzle enough,

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:06.183 align:middle line:84%
it's actually somewhat
intuitive in that you

00:36:06.183 --> 00:36:07.830 align:middle line:84%
can get where it's
almost sorted,

00:36:07.830 --> 00:36:09.660 align:middle line:84%
but there's just one
pair that's wrong.

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:10.940 align:middle line:84%
So you might think,
well, maybe there's

00:36:10.940 --> 00:36:12.540 align:middle line:84%
something about
these inverted pairs.

00:36:12.540 --> 00:36:14.190 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
them in general,

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:17.070 align:middle line:84%
not just about 0-versus-1
inverted pairs.

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:18.240 align:middle line:90%
But let's count them.

00:36:18.240 --> 00:36:22.100 align:middle line:84%
So over here, we had
one inverted pair.

00:36:22.100 --> 00:36:24.000 align:middle line:90%
Here we had zero inverted pairs.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:25.710 align:middle line:90%
Here we had four inverted pairs.

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:28.250 align:middle line:84%
And I claim it was possible
to go from four inverted pairs

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:33.140 align:middle line:84%
to zero but impossible to go
from one inverted pair to zero.

00:36:33.140 --> 00:36:35.870 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:37.705 align:middle line:90%
Parity, it turns out.

00:36:37.705 --> 00:36:41.000 align:middle line:90%


00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.660 align:middle line:90%
"Parity" means odd or even.

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:54.660 align:middle line:84%
So P of q is going
to be that the number

00:36:54.660 --> 00:37:07.200 align:middle line:84%
of inverted pairs in state
q is odd, turns out to be.

00:37:07.200 --> 00:37:09.250 align:middle line:84%
This proof will
work for either one.

00:37:09.250 --> 00:37:12.640 align:middle line:84%
But if we want to prove this
particular impossibility result,

00:37:12.640 --> 00:37:14.580 align:middle line:90%
odd is what we need.

00:37:14.580 --> 00:37:20.940 align:middle line:84%
So p of q is going to be
true for this configuration

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:23.050 align:middle line:84%
because it has an odd
number of inverted pairs.

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:26.550 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to be
false for these two.

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:28.086 align:middle line:90%
Why is that interesting?

00:37:28.086 --> 00:37:31.620 align:middle line:90%


00:37:31.620 --> 00:37:41.070 align:middle line:84%
Because over here, we said,
suppose we can show that P of q

00:37:41.070 --> 00:37:42.190 align:middle line:90%
is invariant.

00:37:42.190 --> 00:37:43.770 align:middle line:90%
I claim that's true.

00:37:43.770 --> 00:37:47.130 align:middle line:84%
If we start from
here, where P of q

00:37:47.130 --> 00:37:53.010 align:middle line:84%
starts true, because the number
of inverted pairs starts odd,

00:37:53.010 --> 00:37:57.990 align:middle line:84%
and we find another state
where P of r is false,

00:37:57.990 --> 00:37:59.760 align:middle line:84%
because here the number
of inverted pairs

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:03.400 align:middle line:84%
is even instead of odd,
then r is unreachable.

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:05.760 align:middle line:84%
That means it's impossible
to get from this state

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:06.490 align:middle line:90%
to this state.

00:38:06.490 --> 00:38:08.670 align:middle line:90%
That's what we want to prove.

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:12.160 align:middle line:84%
So if we can prove this
invariant property,

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:16.710 align:middle line:84%
we can plug it into here and get
the puzzle impossibility result

00:38:16.710 --> 00:38:18.720 align:middle line:90%
that we want.

00:38:18.720 --> 00:38:21.510 align:middle line:84%
That's where everything's
going to come together.

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:28.350 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove that P of q is--

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:30.820 align:middle line:84%
ideally, we'd like
it to be invariant.

00:38:30.820 --> 00:38:32.880 align:middle line:84%
But to prove
invariant, we're going

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:34.946 align:middle line:84%
to start with proving
that it's preserved.

00:38:34.946 --> 00:38:57.810 align:middle line:90%


00:38:57.810 --> 00:38:59.460 align:middle line:84%
The reason for the
8 puzzle, that I

00:38:59.460 --> 00:39:02.920 align:middle line:84%
want to talk about preserved
first, is to be invariant,

00:39:02.920 --> 00:39:04.600 align:middle line:90%
it depends where you start.

00:39:04.600 --> 00:39:07.900 align:middle line:90%
And that's a little arbitrary.

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:10.450 align:middle line:84%
There isn't one natural
start state for the 8 puzzle.

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:11.620 align:middle line:90%
You might start here.

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:12.610 align:middle line:90%
You might start here.

00:39:12.610 --> 00:39:13.840 align:middle line:90%
You might start here.

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:16.550 align:middle line:90%
That'd be a very easy puzzle.

00:39:16.550 --> 00:39:20.260 align:middle line:84%
But preserved is just a general
property about the system.

00:39:20.260 --> 00:39:23.220 align:middle line:84%
So I don't need to
assume anything for that.

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:24.820 align:middle line:90%
So we want to do this part.

00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:26.620 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove P
of q is preserved.

00:39:26.620 --> 00:39:30.790 align:middle line:84%
So we consider any transition
q to r where P of q is true.

00:39:30.790 --> 00:39:33.780 align:middle line:90%
We need to prove P of r is true.

00:39:33.780 --> 00:39:39.340 align:middle line:84%
So here, let me plug in the
outline of step 2 there.

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:45.260 align:middle line:84%
Consider any transition
q to r that's valid,

00:39:45.260 --> 00:39:52.330 align:middle line:90%
it's in T, where P of q is true.

00:39:52.330 --> 00:39:55.830 align:middle line:84%
And we want to show
P of r is true.

00:39:55.830 --> 00:39:59.590 align:middle line:90%


00:39:59.590 --> 00:40:03.370 align:middle line:84%
What do transitions
look like in this game?

00:40:03.370 --> 00:40:06.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, relative to reading order,
reading order talks about rows.

00:40:06.890 --> 00:40:10.550 align:middle line:84%
So there's really two types
of moves we care about.

00:40:10.550 --> 00:40:12.410 align:middle line:84%
There's horizontal
moves left and right.

00:40:12.410 --> 00:40:14.240 align:middle line:84%
And there's vertical
moves up and down.

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:18.370 align:middle line:84%
I claim those are
the two cases that we

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:19.990 align:middle line:84%
need to think
about because we're

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:22.540 align:middle line:90%
thinking about reading order.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:29.020 align:middle line:84%
So case 1 is that this
transition, q to r,

00:40:29.020 --> 00:40:30.480 align:middle line:90%
is a horizontal move.

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:39.820 align:middle line:90%


00:40:39.820 --> 00:40:40.850 align:middle line:90%
Horizontal move.

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:45.830 align:middle line:84%
So this is like we take some
number i, and next to it

00:40:45.830 --> 00:40:46.940 align:middle line:90%
there's an x.

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:51.910 align:middle line:84%
And maybe if we move to the
right, that would be x i.

00:40:51.910 --> 00:40:55.090 align:middle line:84%
Or if we move to the left,
it would be like that.

00:40:55.090 --> 00:40:57.070 align:middle line:84%
It's one of those
two transitions.

00:40:57.070 --> 00:40:59.260 align:middle line:90%
x here means the blank.

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.110 align:middle line:84%
How does that change
reading order?

00:41:01.110 --> 00:41:05.650 align:middle line:90%


00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:06.400 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:07.320 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Nothing.

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:08.810 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: Nothing.

00:41:08.810 --> 00:41:09.860 align:middle line:90%
Nothing changes.

00:41:09.860 --> 00:41:11.835 align:middle line:90%
The reading order is the same.

00:41:11.835 --> 00:41:13.460 align:middle line:84%
When we're talking
about reading order,

00:41:13.460 --> 00:41:15.770 align:middle line:84%
we're only talking
about the numbers.

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:17.620 align:middle line:90%
We don't care about the x.

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:32.440 align:middle line:84%
So no changes in reading
order or in the number

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:39.460 align:middle line:84%
of inverted pairs because that's
only dependent on reading order.

00:41:39.460 --> 00:41:42.790 align:middle line:90%
So we have P of r.

00:41:42.790 --> 00:41:46.030 align:middle line:90%
Case 1 is easy.

00:41:46.030 --> 00:41:50.865 align:middle line:84%
Let's prove case
2 maybe over here.

00:41:50.865 --> 00:41:57.190 align:middle line:90%


00:41:57.190 --> 00:41:58.760 align:middle line:90%
Case 2 is a vertical move here.

00:41:58.760 --> 00:42:00.910 align:middle line:84%
There's actually
something to show--

00:42:00.910 --> 00:42:07.830 align:middle line:84%
more interesting,
but not much harder.

00:42:07.830 --> 00:42:23.440 align:middle line:90%


00:42:23.440 --> 00:42:27.940 align:middle line:84%
OK, I'm going to draw some
pictures for intuition.

00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:32.570 align:middle line:84%
It could be we
are moving i down,

00:42:32.570 --> 00:42:36.260 align:middle line:84%
and there's two things
to the right of i.

00:42:36.260 --> 00:42:42.830 align:middle line:84%
It could be we're moving
i in the middle, to here.

00:42:42.830 --> 00:42:49.780 align:middle line:84%
Or it could be we're moving
i on the right, down to here.

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:53.690 align:middle line:90%


00:42:53.690 --> 00:42:56.930 align:middle line:90%
And this is for a down move.

00:42:56.930 --> 00:42:58.350 align:middle line:90%
Up is going to be symmetric.

00:42:58.350 --> 00:43:00.570 align:middle line:84%
But let's first think
about down moves.

00:43:00.570 --> 00:43:04.170 align:middle line:84%
So in order to do a down
move, in reading order,

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:06.620 align:middle line:84%
there are two items
that come after i.

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:09.840 align:middle line:84%
Because we're moving down,
there is something after i.

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:12.990 align:middle line:84%
There's a whole row
after i until this x.

00:43:12.990 --> 00:43:16.850 align:middle line:84%
So if we can move i down,
there's two numbers between i

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:19.260 align:middle line:90%
and the x in reading order.

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:21.860 align:middle line:84%
And i starts before those
numbers if we're going down

00:43:21.860 --> 00:43:24.170 align:middle line:90%
and ends after.

00:43:24.170 --> 00:43:29.926 align:middle line:84%
So the move here, we can
think of it as swapping--

00:43:29.926 --> 00:43:32.660 align:middle line:90%


00:43:32.660 --> 00:43:36.150 align:middle line:90%
we want to swap i with x.

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:46.790 align:middle line:84%
But this is equivalent to
swapping i with j, first of all,

00:43:46.790 --> 00:43:50.720 align:middle line:90%
and then swapping i with k.

00:43:50.720 --> 00:43:53.340 align:middle line:90%
Instead of going straight down--

00:43:53.340 --> 00:43:55.550 align:middle line:90%
and another color--

00:43:55.550 --> 00:43:58.760 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to think of swapping
i to first come after j

00:43:58.760 --> 00:44:00.270 align:middle line:90%
and then come after k.

00:44:00.270 --> 00:44:01.550 align:middle line:90%
That's the same as the x.

00:44:01.550 --> 00:44:03.690 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't matter
where we started.

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:05.940 align:middle line:84%
It could be here,
and then we go here.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:12.530 align:middle line:84%
Or it could be here, we go
after j, and then we go after k.

00:44:12.530 --> 00:44:14.280 align:middle line:90%
The point is if we swap--

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:17.120 align:middle line:84%
if we figure out how to swap
two adjacent numbers in reading

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:22.400 align:middle line:84%
order and we swap i twice,
then i gets to where the x is

00:44:22.400 --> 00:44:25.730 align:middle line:90%
because this is a 3-by-3.

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:28.010 align:middle line:90%
That's why twice.

00:44:28.010 --> 00:44:41.900 align:middle line:84%
So now what we care about is
what happens when we swap two

00:44:41.900 --> 00:44:59.630 align:middle line:84%
adjacent items in reading order,
so not adjacent in the 3-by-3

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:02.070 align:middle line:84%
grid but adjacent
in reading order.

00:45:02.070 --> 00:45:03.210 align:middle line:90%
That's what we care about.

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:05.850 align:middle line:84%
If we can solve this
and we do it twice,

00:45:05.850 --> 00:45:10.590 align:middle line:84%
then we will know what happens
when we do a vertical move.

00:45:10.590 --> 00:45:13.740 align:middle line:84%
So what happens when I
swap two numbers i and j?

00:45:13.740 --> 00:45:15.690 align:middle line:84%
How does that change
the reading order?

00:45:15.690 --> 00:45:16.800 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it swaps i and j.

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:17.820 align:middle line:90%
That's all.

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:19.620 align:middle line:84%
Everything before i
is still before i.

00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:21.630 align:middle line:84%
Everything after j
is still after j.

00:45:21.630 --> 00:45:23.390 align:middle line:84%
The only thing is
we're changing--

00:45:23.390 --> 00:45:25.850 align:middle line:84%
if they're adjacent
items i and j,

00:45:25.850 --> 00:45:30.220 align:middle line:84%
we're only flipping
whether ij is inverted.

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:33.010 align:middle line:84%
If ij was in the correct order
before, if i was less than j,

00:45:33.010 --> 00:45:35.790 align:middle line:84%
then, after I do the swap,
they're an inverted pair.

00:45:35.790 --> 00:45:37.690 align:middle line:84%
If they were an
inverted pair initially,

00:45:37.690 --> 00:45:40.330 align:middle line:84%
if i is bigger than j,
after I do the swap,

00:45:40.330 --> 00:45:42.900 align:middle line:84%
they're no longer
an inverted pair.

00:45:42.900 --> 00:45:47.310 align:middle line:84%
So swapping two
adjacent items changes

00:45:47.310 --> 00:45:58.445 align:middle line:84%
the number of inverted
pairs by plus or minus 1.

00:45:58.445 --> 00:46:02.250 align:middle line:90%


00:46:02.250 --> 00:46:06.070 align:middle line:84%
If they were inverted before,
it decreases the number.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:08.830 align:middle line:84%
If they weren't inverted
before, it increases the number,

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:10.980 align:middle line:90%
but always by one.

00:46:10.980 --> 00:46:12.370 align:middle line:90%
Never stays the same.

00:46:12.370 --> 00:46:16.032 align:middle line:90%
Never changes by seven.

00:46:16.032 --> 00:46:17.860 align:middle line:84%
So when we swap
two adjacent pairs,

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:19.300 align:middle line:90%
we change by plus or minus 1.

00:46:19.300 --> 00:46:20.910 align:middle line:84%
When we do a
vertical move, we do

00:46:20.910 --> 00:46:28.170 align:middle line:84%
we want to do two of
these adjacent swaps.

00:46:28.170 --> 00:46:29.555 align:middle line:90%
So let's continue over here.

00:46:29.555 --> 00:46:33.480 align:middle line:90%


00:46:33.480 --> 00:46:41.280 align:middle line:84%
So if we do two
adjacent swaps, this

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:46.680 align:middle line:84%
will change the number of
inverted pairs by plus or minus

00:46:46.680 --> 00:46:52.398 align:middle line:90%
1, plus plus or minus 1.

00:46:52.398 --> 00:46:53.940 align:middle line:84%
Were each of these
pluses or minuses?

00:46:53.940 --> 00:46:54.700 align:middle line:90%
We don't know.

00:46:54.700 --> 00:46:56.430 align:middle line:90%
They could be plus or minus.

00:46:56.430 --> 00:47:00.960 align:middle line:84%
But the point is plus or
minus 1 is an odd number.

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:03.220 align:middle line:84%
Plus or minus 1
is an odd number.

00:47:03.220 --> 00:47:06.020 align:middle line:84%
When I add two odd numbers,
this is an even number.

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:08.880 align:middle line:90%


00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:11.110 align:middle line:84%
Turns out you can
draw a little picture.

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:14.820 align:middle line:84%
If we start at 0 here and we
do plus or minus 1, and then

00:47:14.820 --> 00:47:18.630 align:middle line:84%
from here we do plus or
minus 1, and from here we

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:20.400 align:middle line:84%
do plus or minus
1-- this is a case

00:47:20.400 --> 00:47:23.730 align:middle line:84%
analysis of all the things
you could do-- you either get

00:47:23.730 --> 00:47:28.680 align:middle line:90%
2 or 0 or minus 2.

00:47:28.680 --> 00:47:31.810 align:middle line:84%
These three numbers
are all even.

00:47:31.810 --> 00:47:33.430 align:middle line:90%
But I don't particularly care.

00:47:33.430 --> 00:47:36.228 align:middle line:84%
It happens to be just
these three values.

00:47:36.228 --> 00:47:37.895 align:middle line:84%
What I care is that
this number is even.

00:47:37.895 --> 00:47:42.300 align:middle line:90%


00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:46.980 align:middle line:84%
We started with P of q
being true over here.

00:47:46.980 --> 00:47:48.970 align:middle line:90%
Assume that P of q is true.

00:47:48.970 --> 00:47:51.960 align:middle line:84%
That means that the number
of inverted pairs in state q

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:53.110 align:middle line:90%
is odd.

00:47:53.110 --> 00:47:56.760 align:middle line:84%
And now we change that
number by an even amount.

00:47:56.760 --> 00:48:01.440 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, it will be odd still.

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:06.280 align:middle line:84%
If we take an odd number, we add
an even number, it stays odd.

00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:11.040 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, P of r is true.

00:48:11.040 --> 00:48:11.760 align:middle line:90%
Question?

00:48:11.760 --> 00:48:14.310 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What
happens if you swap--

00:48:14.310 --> 00:48:17.690 align:middle line:90%
if you swapped the i and the j?

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:20.023 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: So the question
is, why is this two swaps?

00:48:20.023 --> 00:48:23.530 align:middle line:90%


00:48:23.530 --> 00:48:25.750 align:middle line:90%
So the funny thing here--

00:48:25.750 --> 00:48:26.570 align:middle line:90%
so it's right.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:28.630 align:middle line:90%
If I swap i and j, then--

00:48:28.630 --> 00:48:32.853 align:middle line:84%
let me maybe draw a
picture somewhere here.

00:48:32.853 --> 00:48:37.720 align:middle line:90%


00:48:37.720 --> 00:48:39.070 align:middle line:90%
Let's just go here.

00:48:39.070 --> 00:48:40.160 align:middle line:90%
Scratch space.

00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:45.340 align:middle line:84%
So if we have i, j, k,
x, and I swap i and j,

00:48:45.340 --> 00:48:49.990 align:middle line:90%
then I get j, i, k, x.

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:51.950 align:middle line:90%
And then I swap i and k.

00:48:51.950 --> 00:48:55.810 align:middle line:90%
Then I get j, k, i, x.

00:48:55.810 --> 00:49:00.106 align:middle line:84%
And you're right, i is
not quite where I want it.

00:49:00.106 --> 00:49:01.910 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES] This is funny.

00:49:01.910 --> 00:49:07.180 align:middle line:84%
I really want i
to be here, which

00:49:07.180 --> 00:49:14.640 align:middle line:84%
I can do like this because that
doesn't change reading order.

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:16.520 align:middle line:84%
OK, it's good that
we spelled this out.

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:18.920 align:middle line:84%
And also, I can do
horizontal moves for free.

00:49:18.920 --> 00:49:23.500 align:middle line:90%
So j, k, i.

00:49:23.500 --> 00:49:27.020 align:middle line:84%
This is maybe a way
to think about it.

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:31.780 align:middle line:84%
The point is that these three
have the same reading order.

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:33.970 align:middle line:90%
So those don't really count.

00:49:33.970 --> 00:49:37.377 align:middle line:84%
But I'm glad you
had me spell it out.

00:49:37.377 --> 00:49:39.460 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the [INAUDIBLE]
we're doing right now

00:49:39.460 --> 00:49:41.520 align:middle line:84%
are not part of the
valid transition.

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:43.040 align:middle line:90%
It's just to just separate them?

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:43.873 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: Right.

00:49:43.873 --> 00:49:47.030 align:middle line:84%
These are not valid
transitions, indeed.

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:50.030 align:middle line:84%
At the end, we get to something
that's a valid transition.

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:53.300 align:middle line:84%
So the transition goes
from here directly to here.

00:49:53.300 --> 00:49:55.270 align:middle line:84%
And we're splitting
it up into some sub

00:49:55.270 --> 00:49:58.000 align:middle line:84%
moves that aren't valid
moves by themselves

00:49:58.000 --> 00:49:59.270 align:middle line:90%
but easier to analyze.

00:49:59.270 --> 00:50:02.110 align:middle line:84%
First, we think about what
happens when we swap i and j.

00:50:02.110 --> 00:50:03.980 align:middle line:90%
That changes by plus or minus 1.

00:50:03.980 --> 00:50:07.370 align:middle line:90%
Then we swap i and k.

00:50:07.370 --> 00:50:09.933 align:middle line:84%
That changes these
by a plus or minus 1.

00:50:09.933 --> 00:50:11.350 align:middle line:84%
Then we do these
horizontal moves,

00:50:11.350 --> 00:50:15.500 align:middle line:84%
which doesn't change
anything, or horizontal moves.

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:20.630 align:middle line:84%
Moving the x in reading order
doesn't change anything.

00:50:20.630 --> 00:50:23.020 align:middle line:90%
Cool?

00:50:23.020 --> 00:50:25.410 align:middle line:90%
All right, great.

00:50:25.410 --> 00:50:29.560 align:middle line:90%


00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:31.790 align:middle line:84%
I feel like I skipped a
little bit of a step here.

00:50:31.790 --> 00:50:37.720 align:middle line:90%


00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:40.550 align:middle line:90%
So the point is, when we swap--

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:47.130 align:middle line:84%
in case 2, when we
do a vertical move,

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:53.470 align:middle line:84%
we started with an odd
number of inverted pairs.

00:50:53.470 --> 00:50:57.430 align:middle line:90%
And then we add an even number.

00:50:57.430 --> 00:51:00.500 align:middle line:90%
And odd plus even equals odd.

00:51:00.500 --> 00:51:03.340 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, P of r is true.

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:05.230 align:middle line:90%
That's the point.

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:07.840 align:middle line:84%
So if we start odd,
we will stay odd.

00:51:07.840 --> 00:51:10.420 align:middle line:84%
If you swap odd and
even in this proof,

00:51:10.420 --> 00:51:15.160 align:middle line:84%
you can also show that if you
start even, you stay even.

00:51:15.160 --> 00:51:20.100 align:middle line:84%
But what we really want
is, for this part here,

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:23.870 align:middle line:84%
we want to get P of q to be
invariant and find a place where

00:51:23.870 --> 00:51:26.820 align:middle line:84%
P is false, and then conclude
that r is unreachable.

00:51:26.820 --> 00:51:28.390 align:middle line:90%
So let's do that quickly.

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:31.730 align:middle line:90%


00:51:31.730 --> 00:51:38.660 align:middle line:84%
So let's define
this state to be q0.

00:51:38.660 --> 00:51:41.240 align:middle line:90%


00:51:41.240 --> 00:51:43.323 align:middle line:90%
So for this q0, we have--

00:51:43.323 --> 00:51:47.510 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.510 --> 00:51:56.430 align:middle line:84%
or maybe let's say if P of q0
is true, as in this example

00:51:56.430 --> 00:52:03.110 align:middle line:84%
because there's an odd number
of inverted pairs, then P of q

00:52:03.110 --> 00:52:04.626 align:middle line:90%
is invariant.

00:52:04.626 --> 00:52:09.170 align:middle line:90%


00:52:09.170 --> 00:52:18.470 align:middle line:84%
And so by this property,
if P of r is false,

00:52:18.470 --> 00:52:23.586 align:middle line:90%
then r is unreachable.

00:52:23.586 --> 00:52:26.960 align:middle line:90%


00:52:26.960 --> 00:52:28.670 align:middle line:84%
So actually what I
care about is not

00:52:28.670 --> 00:52:31.383 align:middle line:84%
p of r but P of the
final state, qf.

00:52:31.383 --> 00:52:35.300 align:middle line:90%


00:52:35.300 --> 00:52:37.045 align:middle line:90%
So that's exactly the scenario.

00:52:37.045 --> 00:52:38.420 align:middle line:84%
We start in a
state where we have

00:52:38.420 --> 00:52:39.750 align:middle line:90%
an odd number of transitions.

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:45.630 align:middle line:84%
We're trying to get to a state
with zero inverted pairs.

00:52:45.630 --> 00:52:48.770 align:middle line:84%
And so that's not
going to be possible

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:50.730 align:middle line:90%
because we start with P true.

00:52:50.730 --> 00:52:55.010 align:middle line:84%
And we somehow are trying to
reach a state where P is false.

00:52:55.010 --> 00:53:00.140 align:middle line:84%
But if we can prove this
invariant property--

00:53:00.140 --> 00:53:02.490 align:middle line:84%
and we've basically done
all the hard work here.

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:04.800 align:middle line:84%
This is just by the
invariant principle.

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:07.090 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm following the
outline over on the left.

00:53:07.090 --> 00:53:11.510 align:middle line:90%


00:53:11.510 --> 00:53:16.200 align:middle line:84%
Step 1 is-- or part 1
is that P of q0 is true.

00:53:16.200 --> 00:53:17.570 align:middle line:90%
We assume that.

00:53:17.570 --> 00:53:23.630 align:middle line:84%
Step 2 is that P
of q is preserved.

00:53:23.630 --> 00:53:25.160 align:middle line:90%
And we just proved that.

00:53:25.160 --> 00:53:26.995 align:middle line:90%
This is our theorem.

00:53:26.995 --> 00:53:29.510 align:middle line:90%


00:53:29.510 --> 00:53:31.670 align:middle line:84%
So maybe you don't know
this word, "corollary"--

00:53:31.670 --> 00:53:33.840 align:middle line:84%
or "cor-aw-luh-ree"
if you're Canadian.

00:53:33.840 --> 00:53:36.330 align:middle line:84%
"Corollary" means
something that follows.

00:53:36.330 --> 00:53:38.250 align:middle line:84%
So "theorem" means
something that's true.

00:53:38.250 --> 00:53:40.760 align:middle line:84%
Both of these are
supposed to be true.

00:53:40.760 --> 00:53:43.970 align:middle line:84%
But these are words to say that
a theorem was the main thing we

00:53:43.970 --> 00:53:44.880 align:middle line:90%
wanted to prove.

00:53:44.880 --> 00:53:46.400 align:middle line:84%
And then corollary
is something that

00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:47.640 align:middle line:90%
follows immediately from it.

00:53:47.640 --> 00:53:49.650 align:middle line:84%
It's almost a
one-line proof here.

00:53:49.650 --> 00:53:53.270 align:middle line:84%
Once we have the theorem,
the corollary is immediate.

00:53:53.270 --> 00:53:55.470 align:middle line:90%
It's just some terminology.

00:53:55.470 --> 00:53:58.736 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully you now
believe this is impossible.

00:53:58.736 --> 00:54:02.510 align:middle line:90%


00:54:02.510 --> 00:54:04.540 align:middle line:84%
Any questions
about the 8 puzzle?

00:54:04.540 --> 00:54:08.420 align:middle line:90%


00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:11.340 align:middle line:84%
For fun, let's solve
it one more time.

00:54:11.340 --> 00:54:15.420 align:middle line:84%
I actually didn't have time this
morning to implement the "only

00:54:15.420 --> 00:54:16.930 align:middle line:90%
generate solvable puzzles."

00:54:16.930 --> 00:54:19.360 align:middle line:84%
So I have no idea whether
this will be solvable.

00:54:19.360 --> 00:54:20.400 align:middle line:90%
It's kind of exciting.

00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:24.570 align:middle line:84%
If you can count the inversions,
you'll figure it out.

00:54:24.570 --> 00:54:27.840 align:middle line:84%
But I keep moving it,
so it's pretty hard.

00:54:27.840 --> 00:54:30.780 align:middle line:84%
And I'm following a
