00:54:38.800 --> 00:54:39.360 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:54:39.360 --> 00:54:43.680 align:middle line:84%
So I must have started with an
even number of inverted pairs.

00:54:43.680 --> 00:54:47.070 align:middle line:84%
In a future version, I
will add that number.

00:54:47.070 --> 00:54:48.195 align:middle line:90%
But there we go.

00:54:48.195 --> 00:54:48.695 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:54:48.695 --> 00:54:51.705 align:middle line:90%


00:54:51.705 --> 00:54:52.205 align:middle line:90%
Question?

00:54:52.205 --> 00:54:55.590 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
final stage [INAUDIBLE]?

00:54:55.590 --> 00:55:01.482 align:middle line:90%


00:55:01.482 --> 00:55:03.690 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: So your question
is, if, in this state,

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:06.820 align:middle line:84%
we move six down, how many
inverted pairs do we get?

00:55:06.820 --> 00:55:07.670 align:middle line:90%
Let's draw it.

00:55:07.670 --> 00:55:10.710 align:middle line:90%


00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:15.790 align:middle line:90%
So that is 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, x.

00:55:15.790 --> 00:55:18.770 align:middle line:90%
It should be 2.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:21.100 align:middle line:90%
7, 8, 6.

00:55:21.100 --> 00:55:22.830 align:middle line:84%
How many inverted
pairs are there?

00:55:22.830 --> 00:55:24.900 align:middle line:90%
7 is inverted with 6.

00:55:24.900 --> 00:55:26.620 align:middle line:90%
8 is inverted with 6.

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:28.410 align:middle line:90%
And that's it.

00:55:28.410 --> 00:55:30.310 align:middle line:90%
So there's an example in action.

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:32.080 align:middle line:90%
Vertical move, changing by 2.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:33.900 align:middle line:90%
Sometimes it changes by 0.

00:55:33.900 --> 00:55:37.030 align:middle line:84%
If i is sandwiched in
between j and k numerically,

00:55:37.030 --> 00:55:40.350 align:middle line:84%
sometimes it changes
by plus or minus 2.

00:55:40.350 --> 00:55:44.880 align:middle line:84%
Of course, if we do the
up move, we subtract 2.

00:55:44.880 --> 00:55:46.030 align:middle line:90%
There was another question.

00:55:46.030 --> 00:55:47.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:55:47.350 --> 00:55:49.470 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you
explain the definition

00:55:49.470 --> 00:55:51.100 align:middle line:90%
of preservation and invariance?

00:55:51.100 --> 00:55:54.400 align:middle line:90%
And [INAUDIBLE]?

00:55:54.400 --> 00:55:59.290 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: OK, question is
explain preserved and invariant.

00:55:59.290 --> 00:56:02.645 align:middle line:84%
And where are we using
the different parts?

00:56:02.645 --> 00:56:06.060 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.060 --> 00:56:10.020 align:middle line:84%
If I can make an induction
analogy for a second,

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:13.050 align:middle line:90%
preserved means--

00:56:13.050 --> 00:56:14.530 align:middle line:90%
is like your induction step.

00:56:14.530 --> 00:56:17.770 align:middle line:84%
It says, every time you do a
transition, if P started true,

00:56:17.770 --> 00:56:19.230 align:middle line:90%
it remains true.

00:56:19.230 --> 00:56:22.883 align:middle line:84%
And invariant is what you
get out of the induction.

00:56:22.883 --> 00:56:24.800 align:middle line:84%
Let's go over to the
invariant principle here.

00:56:24.800 --> 00:56:28.020 align:middle line:90%


00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:29.640 align:middle line:84%
The invariant
principle basically

00:56:29.640 --> 00:56:31.300 align:middle line:84%
says preserved
implies invariant,

00:56:31.300 --> 00:56:34.290 align:middle line:84%
except you also need to
check that you start true.

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:37.560 align:middle line:84%
If P starts true and
whenever you do a transition

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:41.370 align:middle line:84%
it remains true,
then it's always

00:56:41.370 --> 00:56:44.250 align:middle line:90%
true for every reachable state.

00:56:44.250 --> 00:56:46.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, so crucially in
this setup, we're

00:56:46.590 --> 00:56:49.080 align:middle line:84%
ignoring all the
unreachable states,

00:56:49.080 --> 00:56:52.420 align:middle line:84%
just talking-- invariant only
talks about reachable states.

00:56:52.420 --> 00:56:55.860 align:middle line:84%
It says that every
reachable state P is true.

00:56:55.860 --> 00:56:58.060 align:middle line:84%
That's what we're
concluding from,

00:56:58.060 --> 00:57:00.570 align:middle line:84%
we start true, and every
time we start in a true state

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:03.390 align:middle line:84%
and we make a transition,
we remain true.

00:57:03.390 --> 00:57:06.520 align:middle line:90%
Hopefully that's clear.

00:57:06.520 --> 00:57:08.890 align:middle line:84%
Takes a little while
to get comfortable

00:57:08.890 --> 00:57:11.712 align:middle line:84%
with these definitions,
but very important,

00:57:11.712 --> 00:57:13.670 align:middle line:84%
the difference between
preserved and invariant.

00:57:13.670 --> 00:57:17.650 align:middle line:84%
So if you forget, read
the definition, or just

00:57:17.650 --> 00:57:19.145 align:middle line:90%
follow this template.

00:57:19.145 --> 00:57:20.270 align:middle line:90%
This makes it pretty clear.

00:57:20.270 --> 00:57:22.150 align:middle line:84%
Usually, we just want
to prove invariant.

00:57:22.150 --> 00:57:24.260 align:middle line:90%
And there's a clear start state.

00:57:24.260 --> 00:57:27.430 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, the next
example will have a--

00:57:27.430 --> 00:57:29.000 align:middle line:90%
well, no, that's not true.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:30.770 align:middle line:84%
But if there's a
clear start state,

00:57:30.770 --> 00:57:32.420 align:middle line:84%
you can just follow
this template.

00:57:32.420 --> 00:57:36.160 align:middle line:84%
And all you care about
is proving invariant.

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:42.216 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's do the next
topic, which is termination.

00:57:42.216 --> 00:58:01.210 align:middle line:90%


00:58:01.210 --> 00:58:09.970 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I want to start
with an example, which

00:58:09.970 --> 00:58:12.126 align:middle line:90%
is a simple sort of machine.

00:58:12.126 --> 00:58:17.650 align:middle line:90%


00:58:17.650 --> 00:58:20.110 align:middle line:90%
This is another state machine.

00:58:20.110 --> 00:58:23.470 align:middle line:90%
And it sorts n numbers.

00:58:23.470 --> 00:58:24.970 align:middle line:84%
This is a problem
you study a lot

00:58:24.970 --> 00:58:28.245 align:middle line:84%
in the follow-ons to this
class, the algorithms classes.

00:58:28.245 --> 00:58:32.650 align:middle line:90%


00:58:32.650 --> 00:58:36.970 align:middle line:84%
So suppose we're given a bunch
of real numbers, or integers,

00:58:36.970 --> 00:58:38.890 align:middle line:90%
whatever.

00:58:38.890 --> 00:58:45.765 align:middle line:84%
We want to sort them
in increasing order.

00:58:45.765 --> 00:58:53.710 align:middle line:90%


00:58:53.710 --> 00:58:57.940 align:middle line:84%
OK, here is-- so they're given
in some particular order, a1

00:58:57.940 --> 00:58:58.810 align:middle line:90%
through an.

00:58:58.810 --> 00:59:01.390 align:middle line:84%
And I want to rearrange
them so it has exactly

00:59:01.390 --> 00:59:03.020 align:middle line:90%
the same set of numbers--

00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:06.110 align:middle line:84%
or exactly the same numbers
but in a different order,

00:59:06.110 --> 00:59:07.490 align:middle line:90%
and this time increasing order.

00:59:07.490 --> 00:59:10.090 align:middle line:84%
So I want a1 to be less
than or equal to a2,

00:59:10.090 --> 00:59:12.580 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal
to a3, and so on.

00:59:12.580 --> 00:59:14.650 align:middle line:84%
Here is a very simple
algorithm to do

00:59:14.650 --> 00:59:25.270 align:middle line:84%
that, which is while
there's some index

00:59:25.270 --> 00:59:38.590 align:middle line:84%
i, where ai is bigger than ai
plus 1, swap ai with ai plus 1.

00:59:38.590 --> 00:59:41.050 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just looking
at consecutive pairs

00:59:41.050 --> 00:59:42.650 align:middle line:90%
ai to ai plus 1.

00:59:42.650 --> 00:59:45.430 align:middle line:84%
And if there's some that's
out of order, i is less than i

00:59:45.430 --> 00:59:48.410 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 but ai is
greater than ai plus 1,

00:59:48.410 --> 00:59:50.840 align:middle line:84%
then I want to swap
them in the right order.

00:59:50.840 --> 00:59:55.420 align:middle line:84%
We can see this algorithm
in action for fun.

00:59:55.420 --> 01:00:00.020 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to convert
this algorithm into a state

01:00:00.020 --> 01:00:01.370 align:middle line:90%
machine.

01:00:01.370 --> 01:00:04.500 align:middle line:84%
So just pretend you understand
algorithms for a second.

01:00:04.500 --> 01:00:06.840 align:middle line:84%
Here, we have the numbers
in a particular order.

01:00:06.840 --> 01:00:09.380 align:middle line:84%
The height corresponds to
the value that's written,

01:00:09.380 --> 01:00:11.730 align:middle line:90%
3, 6, 2, 5, 4, 1.

01:00:11.730 --> 01:00:16.100 align:middle line:84%
And we're just going
to do an example.

01:00:16.100 --> 01:00:17.490 align:middle line:90%
But then we do a swap.

01:00:17.490 --> 01:00:20.370 align:middle line:84%
A swap-- we're always
swapping adjacent pairs.

01:00:20.370 --> 01:00:22.310 align:middle line:84%
And then Pac-Man comes
over to the left,

01:00:22.310 --> 01:00:24.840 align:middle line:90%
and we get them in sorted order.

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:28.310 align:middle line:90%
So that is the algorithm.

01:00:28.310 --> 01:00:32.005 align:middle line:84%
Let's now analyze it
as a state machine.

01:00:32.005 --> 01:00:34.970 align:middle line:90%


01:00:34.970 --> 01:00:39.920 align:middle line:84%
So first question is,
what are the states Q?

01:00:39.920 --> 01:00:42.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, throughout
this algorithm-- so

01:00:42.080 --> 01:00:46.520 align:middle line:84%
this is in our head, what
we're thinking about doing.

01:00:46.520 --> 01:00:48.352 align:middle line:90%
And we choose Ii arbitrarily.

01:00:48.352 --> 01:00:50.310 align:middle line:84%
Now we're going to model
it as a state machine.

01:00:50.310 --> 01:00:53.840 align:middle line:84%
This will make precise
what's actually going on.

01:00:53.840 --> 01:00:57.420 align:middle line:84%
As we do this, we're taking the
original items in some order.

01:00:57.420 --> 01:00:59.280 align:middle line:90%
We're always swapping items.

01:00:59.280 --> 01:01:04.130 align:middle line:84%
So at any moment in time, what
we have is some reordering

01:01:04.130 --> 01:01:06.180 align:middle line:90%
of the ai's.

01:01:06.180 --> 01:01:09.200 align:middle line:90%
Those are our states.

01:01:09.200 --> 01:01:12.850 align:middle line:84%
Let's define Q to be
all possible orderings.

01:01:12.850 --> 01:01:15.350 align:middle line:84%
These may not all be reachable,
but this is the thing that's

01:01:15.350 --> 01:01:18.830 align:middle line:90%
easy to define--

01:01:18.830 --> 01:01:22.525 align:middle line:84%
all possible
orderings of a1 to an.

01:01:22.525 --> 01:01:27.800 align:middle line:90%


01:01:27.800 --> 01:01:29.130 align:middle line:90%
For this template--

01:01:29.130 --> 01:01:42.320 align:middle line:90%


01:01:42.320 --> 01:01:44.246 align:middle line:90%
OK, what are the transitions?

01:01:44.246 --> 01:01:58.340 align:middle line:90%


01:01:58.340 --> 01:02:01.910 align:middle line:84%
Transitions are going to
take some ai ai plus one pair

01:02:01.910 --> 01:02:03.890 align:middle line:90%
and swap them.

01:02:03.890 --> 01:02:06.890 align:middle line:84%
So if we start with
them in this order,

01:02:06.890 --> 01:02:11.810 align:middle line:84%
they're going to end up
in the opposite order.

01:02:11.810 --> 01:02:13.970 align:middle line:84%
And we are only
allowed to do this when

01:02:13.970 --> 01:02:19.760 align:middle line:90%
ai is bigger than ai plus 1.

01:02:19.760 --> 01:02:22.820 align:middle line:90%
So that's the transitions.

01:02:22.820 --> 01:02:25.680 align:middle line:84%
Implicitly, this specifies
exactly the algorithm.

01:02:25.680 --> 01:02:28.670 align:middle line:84%
The algorithm says, take
some i where ai is bigger

01:02:28.670 --> 01:02:31.742 align:middle line:90%
than ai plus 1, and swap them.

01:02:31.742 --> 01:02:33.200 align:middle line:84%
That's exactly what
the transitions

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:37.610 align:middle line:84%
specify because we can
take any transition that's

01:02:37.610 --> 01:02:38.940 align:middle line:90%
valid from any state.

01:02:38.940 --> 01:02:43.140 align:middle line:84%
So if we can find any i where
ai is greater than ai plus 1,

01:02:43.140 --> 01:02:45.930 align:middle line:84%
then swapping that pair
is a valid transition.

01:02:45.930 --> 01:02:47.390 align:middle line:90%
We don't know which one will do.

01:02:47.390 --> 01:02:50.000 align:middle line:84%
State machine will
follow some execution

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:54.750 align:middle line:84%
which will do one of these
until it can't anymore.

01:02:54.750 --> 01:02:56.693 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

01:02:56.693 --> 01:03:03.000 align:middle line:90%


01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:04.570 align:middle line:90%
Can't anymore.

01:03:04.570 --> 01:03:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Let's define a tool
which is final states.

01:03:08.570 --> 01:03:15.630 align:middle line:90%


01:03:15.630 --> 01:03:24.090 align:middle line:84%
Let's call a state
q final if there's

01:03:24.090 --> 01:03:31.500 align:middle line:84%
no transition q to r and T,
if there's no transition that

01:03:31.500 --> 01:03:33.310 align:middle line:90%
starts at q and goes somewhere.

01:03:33.310 --> 01:03:36.030 align:middle line:90%


01:03:36.030 --> 01:03:40.180 align:middle line:84%
So in the 8 puzzle, there
are no final states.

01:03:40.180 --> 01:03:41.470 align:middle line:90%
You can always make moves.

01:03:41.470 --> 01:03:42.323 align:middle line:90%
You never are done.

01:03:42.323 --> 01:03:44.740 align:middle line:84%
You're done only when you
happen to reach the final state.

01:03:44.740 --> 01:03:46.500 align:middle line:84%
But there's nothing
in the move definition

01:03:46.500 --> 01:03:49.680 align:middle line:84%
that prevents you
from continuing.

01:03:49.680 --> 01:03:53.480 align:middle line:84%
In this problem, there
are final states.

01:03:53.480 --> 01:04:00.390 align:middle line:90%


01:04:00.390 --> 01:04:10.980 align:middle line:84%
I claim it's exactly a0 to
an, where a1 is less than

01:04:10.980 --> 01:04:13.440 align:middle line:84%
or equal to a2, is less than
or equal to a3, and so on,

01:04:13.440 --> 01:04:18.000 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to
an, namely the sorted order.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:19.320 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:04:19.320 --> 01:04:22.200 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all, I
claim this state is final

01:04:22.200 --> 01:04:25.680 align:middle line:84%
because if you look at any
pair ai, ai plus 1, we have ai

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:27.610 align:middle line:84%
is less than or
equal to ai plus 1.

01:04:27.610 --> 01:04:29.650 align:middle line:84%
So we don't have a
transition out of there.

01:04:29.650 --> 01:04:31.540 align:middle line:84%
So these states are
definitely final.

01:04:31.540 --> 01:04:33.960 align:middle line:84%
I also claim that it's
all the final states

01:04:33.960 --> 01:04:39.870 align:middle line:84%
because if I had some state
where this is not true,

01:04:39.870 --> 01:04:43.200 align:middle line:84%
that means one of these
inequalities is not true.

01:04:43.200 --> 01:04:46.030 align:middle line:84%
So that means there's some ai
that's greater than ai plus 1.

01:04:46.030 --> 01:04:48.240 align:middle line:90%
And then there's a transition.

01:04:48.240 --> 01:04:52.890 align:middle line:84%
So that was a spoken argument
for why the final states are

01:04:52.890 --> 01:04:54.840 align:middle line:90%
exactly this.

01:04:54.840 --> 01:04:58.750 align:middle line:84%
Technically, we're proving
all of these states are final

01:04:58.750 --> 01:05:01.030 align:middle line:84%
and that all final
states are of this form,

01:05:01.030 --> 01:05:04.770 align:middle line:84%
and therefore these are
all the final states.

01:05:04.770 --> 01:05:06.463 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:05:06.463 --> 01:05:09.330 align:middle line:90%


01:05:09.330 --> 01:05:16.827 align:middle line:84%
So this gives us something
we call partially correct.

01:05:16.827 --> 01:05:18.410 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to
define this formally.

01:05:18.410 --> 01:05:22.170 align:middle line:90%


01:05:22.170 --> 01:05:25.890 align:middle line:84%
Partially correct
machine is a machine

01:05:25.890 --> 01:05:32.550 align:middle line:84%
where, if it terminates,
which I haven't defined,

01:05:32.550 --> 01:05:36.575 align:middle line:90%
then gives the correct answer.

01:05:36.575 --> 01:05:43.830 align:middle line:90%


01:05:43.830 --> 01:05:45.365 align:middle line:90%
What does "terminate" mean?

01:05:45.365 --> 01:06:39.400 align:middle line:90%


01:06:39.400 --> 01:06:42.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, to terminate means--

01:06:42.790 --> 01:06:45.460 align:middle line:84%
when we're going to say a state
machine terminates, really what

01:06:45.460 --> 01:06:47.450 align:middle line:84%
we're meaning is it
always terminates.

01:06:47.450 --> 01:06:51.050 align:middle line:84%
No matter how you execute
this machine, it stops.

01:06:51.050 --> 01:06:56.842 align:middle line:84%
And the only way it can stop is
that it reaches a final state.

01:06:56.842 --> 01:06:58.300 align:middle line:84%
If you think about
it for a second,

01:06:58.300 --> 01:07:01.820 align:middle line:84%
the definition of "execution"
was a sequence of transitions.

01:07:01.820 --> 01:07:05.290 align:middle line:84%
And so terminates says
there's no infinite execution.

01:07:05.290 --> 01:07:08.050 align:middle line:84%
For an infinite execution,
that means every state qi,

01:07:08.050 --> 01:07:11.110 align:middle line:84%
there's some transition
out of it to qi plus 1.

01:07:11.110 --> 01:07:14.660 align:middle line:84%
So if that's not possible,
that means that, at some point,

01:07:14.660 --> 01:07:16.900 align:middle line:90%
you reach a state that's final.

01:07:16.900 --> 01:07:20.825 align:middle line:84%
And from there,
there's no transition.

01:07:20.825 --> 01:07:22.450 align:middle line:84%
So you could either
say "it terminates"

01:07:22.450 --> 01:07:25.900 align:middle line:84%
means there's no infinite
execution or every execution

01:07:25.900 --> 01:07:27.230 align:middle line:90%
reaches a final state.

01:07:27.230 --> 01:07:29.166 align:middle line:90%
These turn out to be equivalent.

01:07:29.166 --> 01:07:32.020 align:middle line:90%


01:07:32.020 --> 01:07:35.740 align:middle line:84%
So now I claim what we've shown
is that, for the simple sorter

01:07:35.740 --> 01:07:39.400 align:middle line:84%
machine, it actually sorts in
this partially correct sense

01:07:39.400 --> 01:07:43.030 align:middle line:84%
that if the machine
terminates, then

01:07:43.030 --> 01:07:45.280 align:middle line:84%
it will give the correct
answer because if it reaches

01:07:45.280 --> 01:07:47.690 align:middle line:90%
a final state, it's sorted.

01:07:47.690 --> 01:07:49.840 align:middle line:90%
That's what we just argued.

01:07:49.840 --> 01:07:52.060 align:middle line:90%
Now, that's not enough.

01:07:52.060 --> 01:07:54.290 align:middle line:84%
We also want to show
that it terminates.

01:07:54.290 --> 01:07:58.960 align:middle line:84%
And so really, the
main thing to do--

01:07:58.960 --> 01:08:00.400 align:middle line:90%
the main thing to do--

01:08:00.400 --> 01:08:03.160 align:middle line:90%
is to prove termination.

01:08:03.160 --> 01:08:14.590 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, let's
say a machine is correct

01:08:14.590 --> 01:08:20.380 align:middle line:84%
if it terminates and produces
the right answer, which

01:08:20.380 --> 01:08:21.614 align:middle line:90%
was partially correct.

01:08:21.614 --> 01:08:26.062 align:middle line:90%


01:08:26.062 --> 01:08:27.979 align:middle line:84%
OK, I haven't formally
defined "right answer."

01:08:27.979 --> 01:08:29.646 align:middle line:84%
But for the sorting
problem, it's clear.

01:08:29.646 --> 01:08:34.779 align:middle line:84%
We want to get them in order so
that this holds, a1 is less than

01:08:34.779 --> 01:08:38.859 align:middle line:84%
or equal to a2, is less than
or equal to dot, dot, dot.

01:08:38.859 --> 01:08:40.859 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we've proved
partially correct.

01:08:40.859 --> 01:08:42.090 align:middle line:90%
But we need to prove correct.

01:08:42.090 --> 01:08:47.760 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, we need
to show that it terminates.

01:08:47.760 --> 01:08:52.550 align:middle line:84%
So we need some tools
for proving termination

01:08:52.550 --> 01:08:55.399 align:middle line:90%
for this machine.

01:08:55.399 --> 01:08:56.770 align:middle line:90%
Let's go to another board.

01:08:56.770 --> 01:09:02.540 align:middle line:90%


01:09:02.540 --> 01:09:06.750 align:middle line:84%
We want to make sure that this
algorithm doesn't take forever,

01:09:06.750 --> 01:09:08.330 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't go in
an infinite loop

01:09:08.330 --> 01:09:10.750 align:middle line:84%
and never reaches
the sorted state.

01:09:10.750 --> 01:09:20.930 align:middle line:90%


01:09:20.930 --> 01:09:23.609 align:middle line:84%
Let me define a
general tool for this.

01:09:23.609 --> 01:09:26.079 align:middle line:84%
This is how we will always
prove termination in this class.

01:09:26.079 --> 01:09:42.710 align:middle line:90%


01:09:42.710 --> 01:09:45.740 align:middle line:90%
It's called a derived variable.

01:09:45.740 --> 01:09:48.550 align:middle line:84%
This is a reference to
random variables, which

01:09:48.550 --> 01:09:50.300 align:middle line:84%
we will see when we
get to the probability

01:09:50.300 --> 01:09:51.420 align:middle line:90%
section of the class.

01:09:51.420 --> 01:09:53.420 align:middle line:84%
Lots of forward
references today.

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:54.360 align:middle line:90%
It's very simple.

01:09:54.360 --> 01:10:00.350 align:middle line:84%
It's just, for every state, we
define a real number, x of q,

01:10:00.350 --> 01:10:02.180 align:middle line:90%
however you want.

01:10:02.180 --> 01:10:08.540 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
this is a function

01:10:08.540 --> 01:10:14.258 align:middle line:84%
from the set of states
to the real numbers.

01:10:14.258 --> 01:10:15.800 align:middle line:84%
In our applications,
we're only going

01:10:15.800 --> 01:10:17.837 align:middle line:84%
to think of the
natural numbers here.

01:10:17.837 --> 01:10:19.670 align:middle line:84%
But in general, this
could be a real number.

01:10:19.670 --> 01:10:22.320 align:middle line:90%


01:10:22.320 --> 01:10:25.520 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to call it
a derived variable strictly

01:10:25.520 --> 01:10:42.380 align:middle line:84%
decreasing if whenever we have
a transition from q to r in T--

01:10:42.380 --> 01:10:45.860 align:middle line:90%
it's a valid transition--

01:10:45.860 --> 01:10:52.610 align:middle line:84%
we have x of q is strictly
greater than x of r.

01:10:52.610 --> 01:10:55.560 align:middle line:84%
The new value is strictly
less than the old value.

01:10:55.560 --> 01:10:57.410 align:middle line:90%
That's strictly decreasing.

01:10:57.410 --> 01:10:59.410 align:middle line:84%
This is a very
strange looking colon.

01:10:59.410 --> 01:11:03.371 align:middle line:90%


01:11:03.371 --> 01:11:05.580 align:middle line:84%
So again, this is
about a state machine.

01:11:05.580 --> 01:11:07.470 align:middle line:84%
So we can talk
about transitions.

01:11:07.470 --> 01:11:11.900 align:middle line:84%
And every transition strictly
decreases the derived variable.

01:11:11.900 --> 01:11:14.098 align:middle line:84%
This is going to be our
analog to state predicates

01:11:14.098 --> 01:11:15.140 align:middle line:90%
and preserved invariance.

01:11:15.140 --> 01:11:20.400 align:middle line:84%
State predicates we map to
true and false, or 0 and 1.

01:11:20.400 --> 01:11:22.760 align:middle line:84%
Now we're generalizing
to allow it to map

01:11:22.760 --> 01:11:25.230 align:middle line:90%
to any number, any real number.

01:11:25.230 --> 01:11:27.470 align:middle line:90%
But very similar notion.

01:11:27.470 --> 01:11:29.740 align:middle line:84%
Just we're outside
the Boolean realm now.

01:11:29.740 --> 01:11:33.710 align:middle line:90%


01:11:33.710 --> 01:11:37.770 align:middle line:84%
It's very odd to
talk about strictly

01:11:37.770 --> 01:11:41.140 align:middle line:90%
decreasing for Booleans.

01:11:41.140 --> 01:11:43.350 align:middle line:90%
We need this.

01:11:43.350 --> 01:11:46.820 align:middle line:90%
OK, here is a wonderful theorem.

01:11:46.820 --> 01:11:50.730 align:middle line:90%


01:11:50.730 --> 01:11:52.600 align:middle line:84%
It'll be obvious
once I state it.

01:11:52.600 --> 01:11:55.870 align:middle line:84%
But it's very useful
for proving termination.

01:11:55.870 --> 01:11:57.650 align:middle line:84%
It's how most
termination arguments go.

01:11:57.650 --> 01:12:00.330 align:middle line:90%


01:12:00.330 --> 01:12:06.410 align:middle line:84%
So it says, suppose you have
a derived variable x of q.

01:12:06.410 --> 01:12:14.700 align:middle line:90%


01:12:14.700 --> 01:12:17.456 align:middle line:84%
And suppose it satisfies
two properties.

01:12:17.456 --> 01:12:20.820 align:middle line:90%


01:12:20.820 --> 01:12:26.255 align:middle line:84%
Property 1 is it's actually over
the natural numbers, not reals.

01:12:26.255 --> 01:12:30.240 align:middle line:90%


01:12:30.240 --> 01:12:36.106 align:middle line:84%
And property 2 is that
it's strictly decreasing.

01:12:36.106 --> 01:12:47.310 align:middle line:90%


01:12:47.310 --> 01:12:52.376 align:middle line:90%
Then, state machine terminates.

01:12:52.376 --> 01:13:05.790 align:middle line:90%


01:13:05.790 --> 01:13:07.960 align:middle line:84%
So the "then" is, of
course, what we want.

01:13:07.960 --> 01:13:10.300 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that our
state machine terminates.

01:13:10.300 --> 01:13:12.490 align:middle line:84%
So I claim this is
all you need to show.

01:13:12.490 --> 01:13:15.840 align:middle line:84%
You need to construct some
derived variable where the value

01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:17.020 align:middle line:90%
is always a natural number.

01:13:17.020 --> 01:13:18.690 align:middle line:84%
So crucially, it's
always non-negative.

01:13:18.690 --> 01:13:21.127 align:middle line:90%
And it's always an integer.

01:13:21.127 --> 01:13:23.460 align:middle line:84%
I highlight this instead of
putting it in the definition

01:13:23.460 --> 01:13:25.543 align:middle line:84%
because this is something
we really need to prove.

01:13:25.543 --> 01:13:28.090 align:middle line:84%
This theorem is false if
you allow real numbers.

01:13:28.090 --> 01:13:31.070 align:middle line:84%
It's false if you
allow negative numbers.

01:13:31.070 --> 01:13:33.710 align:middle line:84%
Very important that they're
non-negative integers.

01:13:33.710 --> 01:13:35.480 align:middle line:84%
So that's something
we need to check.

01:13:35.480 --> 01:13:37.930 align:middle line:90%
And it's strictly decreasing.

01:13:37.930 --> 01:13:39.050 align:middle line:90%
That's all we need.

01:13:39.050 --> 01:13:41.710 align:middle line:84%
Then we're guaranteed the
machine will terminate.

01:13:41.710 --> 01:13:43.870 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:13:43.870 --> 01:13:46.690 align:middle line:90%
Any guesses why?

01:13:46.690 --> 01:13:51.040 align:middle line:84%
Why is this guaranteed that
our machine terminates?

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:52.135 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:13:52.135 --> 01:13:54.740 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Well,
when you reach 0,

01:13:54.740 --> 01:13:56.960 align:middle line:84%
if x sub q is
strictly decreasing,

01:13:56.960 --> 01:13:58.190 align:middle line:90%
there's nowhere to decrease.

01:13:58.190 --> 01:14:00.258 align:middle line:84%
So there must be no
more transitions.

01:14:00.258 --> 01:14:01.550 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: That sounds good.

01:14:01.550 --> 01:14:03.880 align:middle line:90%
So when x of q reaches 0--

01:14:03.880 --> 01:14:05.755 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if it does,
but if it reaches 0,

01:14:05.755 --> 01:14:07.880 align:middle line:84%
you definitely can't go
any farther because there's

01:14:07.880 --> 01:14:09.020 align:middle line:90%
no transitions out of 0.

01:14:09.020 --> 01:14:11.780 align:middle line:84%
You can't strictly decrease
from 0 if you're non-negative.

01:14:11.780 --> 01:14:14.075 align:middle line:90%
Why do we get to zero?

01:14:14.075 --> 01:14:14.575 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:14:14.575 --> 01:14:16.130 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: We don't necessarily.

01:14:16.130 --> 01:14:18.560 align:middle line:84%
But based on the construction
of natural numbers,

01:14:18.560 --> 01:14:22.945 align:middle line:84%
we will reach a minimum because
it's bounded below, [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:22.945 --> 01:14:25.400 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: OK, we
don't necessarily reach 0,

01:14:25.400 --> 01:14:27.410 align:middle line:90%
but we get to some minimum.

01:14:27.410 --> 01:14:30.080 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I think these are
all in the right direction.

01:14:30.080 --> 01:14:32.170 align:middle line:84%
I'll write down
what I would call

01:14:32.170 --> 01:14:37.790 align:middle line:84%
a sketch that's thinking about
it kind of the other way around.

01:14:37.790 --> 01:14:41.800 align:middle line:84%
Instead of focusing
on x of q decreasing,

01:14:41.800 --> 01:14:45.800 align:middle line:84%
I want to think about
executions of this machine.

01:14:45.800 --> 01:14:48.290 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove that
the machine terminates.

01:14:48.290 --> 01:14:52.040 align:middle line:84%
That means that there are
no infinite sequences.

01:14:52.040 --> 01:14:55.610 align:middle line:84%
In other words, all
executions have finite length.

01:14:55.610 --> 01:15:11.800 align:middle line:84%
I claim all executions
have length at most x of q0

01:15:11.800 --> 01:15:14.710 align:middle line:84%
because every time I
take a step, every time I

01:15:14.710 --> 01:15:18.410 align:middle line:84%
do a transition, x
decreases by at least one.

01:15:18.410 --> 01:15:21.310 align:middle line:84%
If it starts at x
of q0, it can only

01:15:21.310 --> 01:15:23.607 align:middle line:90%
decrease by 1 that many times.

01:15:23.607 --> 01:15:25.690 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, it will
have to have reached 0,

01:15:25.690 --> 01:15:26.690 align:middle line:90%
and then it has to stop.

01:15:26.690 --> 01:15:28.190 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it stopped earlier.

01:15:28.190 --> 01:15:31.620 align:middle line:84%
But this guarantees
that it stops.

01:15:31.620 --> 01:15:35.880 align:middle line:84%
Every step I make, I strictly
decrease x of q by at least one.

01:15:35.880 --> 01:15:36.840 align:middle line:90%
We start here.

01:15:36.840 --> 01:15:38.250 align:middle line:90%
We can't go below 0.

01:15:38.250 --> 01:15:40.500 align:middle line:84%
So the number of
moves is at most that.

01:15:40.500 --> 01:15:42.440 align:middle line:90%
You can prove this by induction.

01:15:42.440 --> 01:15:45.900 align:middle line:84%
But it's kind of
straightforward.

01:15:45.900 --> 01:15:47.550 align:middle line:90%
So you're in the right idea.

01:15:47.550 --> 01:15:49.640 align:middle line:84%
But this is a
little more precise.

01:15:49.640 --> 01:15:50.180 align:middle line:90%
Great.

01:15:50.180 --> 01:15:52.310 align:middle line:84%
So now let's apply our
termination theorem

01:15:52.310 --> 01:15:54.650 align:middle line:90%
to the simple sorter machine.

01:15:54.650 --> 01:15:58.070 align:middle line:84%
But to do that,
we need to define

01:15:58.070 --> 01:16:00.300 align:middle line:90%
one of these derived variables.

01:16:00.300 --> 01:16:04.850 align:middle line:90%


01:16:04.850 --> 01:16:11.150 align:middle line:84%
And-- [CHUCKLES] --it's
actually this one.

01:16:11.150 --> 01:16:13.320 align:middle line:84%
I'll be mean and
just erase this.

01:16:13.320 --> 01:16:15.740 align:middle line:90%
There's our derived variable.

01:16:15.740 --> 01:16:19.220 align:middle line:90%
I'll rewrite it.

01:16:19.220 --> 01:16:20.840 align:middle line:84%
So there's a reason
these two examples

01:16:20.840 --> 01:16:22.230 align:middle line:90%
are in the same lecture.

01:16:22.230 --> 01:16:26.037 align:middle line:84%
They use the same idea,
which is inverted pairs.

01:16:26.037 --> 01:16:28.120 align:middle line:84%
Oh, perhaps I shouldn't
have erased the definition

01:16:28.120 --> 01:16:29.000 align:middle line:90%
of inverted pairs.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:30.010 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:16:30.010 --> 01:16:35.080 align:middle line:84%
So back to the simple
sorting machine.

01:16:35.080 --> 01:16:39.130 align:middle line:84%
We're going to define
P of q to be the number

01:16:39.130 --> 01:16:45.570 align:middle line:90%
of inverted pairs in state q.

01:16:45.570 --> 01:16:49.840 align:middle line:90%


01:16:49.840 --> 01:16:50.990 align:middle line:90%
That's some number.

01:16:50.990 --> 01:16:52.610 align:middle line:90%
It's a natural number.

01:16:52.610 --> 01:16:55.120 align:middle line:84%
It's always greater
than or equal to 0.

01:16:55.120 --> 01:16:57.580 align:middle line:84%
It's always an integer
because inverted pairs

01:16:57.580 --> 01:16:58.820 align:middle line:90%
were this discrete object.

01:16:58.820 --> 01:17:00.882 align:middle line:90%
It was a set ij--

01:17:00.882 --> 01:17:02.840 align:middle line:84%
oh, maybe I need to
redefine this a little bit.

01:17:02.840 --> 01:17:04.220 align:middle line:90%
It's no longer reading order.

01:17:04.220 --> 01:17:05.900 align:middle line:90%
So what is an inverted pair?

01:17:05.900 --> 01:17:15.100 align:middle line:84%
This is ij, where
i is less than j--

01:17:15.100 --> 01:17:21.250 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- but ai is
greater than aj.

01:17:21.250 --> 01:17:26.640 align:middle line:84%
So i and j here are
indices into this sequence.

01:17:26.640 --> 01:17:30.380 align:middle line:84%
So in this example,
let's say 6, 2

01:17:30.380 --> 01:17:33.720 align:middle line:84%
is inverted because 6
is to the left of 2.

01:17:33.720 --> 01:17:34.963 align:middle line:90%
But 6 is greater than 2.

01:17:34.963 --> 01:17:36.630 align:middle line:84%
And that's the opposite
of what we want.

01:17:36.630 --> 01:17:38.520 align:middle line:90%
But also, 6, 1 is inverted.

01:17:38.520 --> 01:17:40.775 align:middle line:84%
It's not just adjacent
pairs-- all the pairs.

01:17:40.775 --> 01:17:42.150 align:middle line:84%
So there's a bunch
of pairs here.

01:17:42.150 --> 01:17:42.840 align:middle line:90%
How many?

01:17:42.840 --> 01:17:45.570 align:middle line:84%
It's exactly the number
of dots in this diagram.

01:17:45.570 --> 01:17:48.650 align:middle line:84%
Each dot-- which we
construct by taking

01:17:48.650 --> 01:17:50.930 align:middle line:84%
each of these numbers
of the particular height

01:17:50.930 --> 01:17:54.768 align:middle line:84%
and drawing a leftward
ray, a line to the left.

01:17:54.768 --> 01:17:56.310 align:middle line:84%
And every time we
hit another number,

01:17:56.310 --> 01:17:58.830 align:middle line:84%
that means that number
was taller than I was.

01:17:58.830 --> 01:18:01.520 align:middle line:84%
So 1, for example, is
wrong with everybody

01:18:01.520 --> 01:18:04.650 align:middle line:84%
because it's supposed to
be all the way on the left.

01:18:04.650 --> 01:18:06.657 align:middle line:84%
So with this funny
height diagram,

01:18:06.657 --> 01:18:07.740 align:middle line:90%
you just draw these lines.

01:18:07.740 --> 01:18:10.350 align:middle line:84%
Those are the inverted
pairs-- a nice visualization.

01:18:10.350 --> 01:18:11.270 align:middle line:90%
Thanks, Zach.

01:18:11.270 --> 01:18:12.380 align:middle line:90%
TA: And Brynmore.

01:18:12.380 --> 01:18:14.810 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: And Brynmore.

01:18:14.810 --> 01:18:18.900 align:middle line:84%
So now we think about what
happens when we do a swap.

01:18:18.900 --> 01:18:21.390 align:middle line:84%
So for example, here I
swap these two items.

01:18:21.390 --> 01:18:22.020 align:middle line:90%
Oh, great.

01:18:22.020 --> 01:18:25.490 align:middle line:84%
Before, 6 and 2 were
inverted; now they're not.

01:18:25.490 --> 01:18:28.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's all that changed
because in the algorithm,

01:18:28.070 --> 01:18:31.830 align:middle line:84%
in the transitions, we're
only swapping adjacent pairs.

01:18:31.830 --> 01:18:35.400 align:middle line:84%
If I swap it back,
the number increases.

01:18:35.400 --> 01:18:36.950 align:middle line:84%
And now if we watch
this algorithm,

01:18:36.950 --> 01:18:39.170 align:middle line:84%
each time it swaps
an adjacent pair,

01:18:39.170 --> 01:18:44.960 align:middle line:84%
it decreases by 1, the
number of inverted pairs.

01:18:44.960 --> 01:18:48.560 align:middle line:90%
Watch it one more time for fun.

01:18:48.560 --> 01:18:49.666 align:middle line:90%
I love this animation.

01:18:49.666 --> 01:19:05.810 align:middle line:90%


01:19:05.810 --> 01:19:08.640 align:middle line:84%
I claim this P of q is
strictly decreasing.

01:19:08.640 --> 01:19:09.380 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:19:09.380 --> 01:19:12.650 align:middle line:84%
Because every time I
do a transition from q

01:19:12.650 --> 01:19:21.040 align:middle line:84%
to r, P of r is 1
smaller than P of q.

01:19:21.040 --> 01:19:24.920 align:middle line:90%


01:19:24.920 --> 01:19:27.730 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at the definition
of transition over here.

01:19:27.730 --> 01:19:30.890 align:middle line:90%


01:19:30.890 --> 01:19:32.750 align:middle line:84%
When I do a transition
in this algorithm,

01:19:32.750 --> 01:19:35.640 align:middle line:84%
I only swap two
adjacent elements.

01:19:35.640 --> 01:19:39.080 align:middle line:84%
So the inverted pairs with
everything else doesn't change.

01:19:39.080 --> 01:19:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And these guys were
guaranteed inverted.

01:19:41.670 --> 01:19:44.660 align:middle line:84%
I told you that ai was bigger
than ai plus 1 whenever

01:19:44.660 --> 01:19:45.600 align:middle line:90%
I did a transition.

01:19:45.600 --> 01:19:48.960 align:middle line:84%
So I decreased by 1 the
number of inverted pairs here.

01:19:48.960 --> 01:19:53.392 align:middle line:84%
So I strictly decrease by
exactly 1 every single time.

01:19:53.392 --> 01:19:55.350 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, the running
time of this algorithm,

01:19:55.350 --> 01:19:58.760 align:middle line:84%
the number of swaps
that we do is exactly

01:19:58.760 --> 01:20:00.690 align:middle line:90%
the number of inverted pairs.

01:20:00.690 --> 01:20:03.067 align:middle line:84%
But in particular, it
terminates in finite time.

01:20:03.067 --> 01:20:05.150 align:middle line:84%
That's what we get out of
this termination theorem

01:20:05.150 --> 01:20:07.890 align:middle line:84%
because we checked
this function.

01:20:07.890 --> 01:20:10.110 align:middle line:84%
This derived variable
is non-negative.

01:20:10.110 --> 01:20:10.820 align:middle line:90%
It's an integer.

01:20:10.820 --> 01:20:12.420 align:middle line:90%
And it's strictly decreasing.

01:20:12.420 --> 01:20:15.276 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, our sorting
algorithm actually terminates.

01:20:15.276 --> 01:20:15.776 align:middle line:90%
Yay.

01:20:15.776 --> 01:20:18.407 align:middle line:90%


01:20:18.407 --> 01:20:20.490 align:middle line:84%
I was supposed to do an
announcement about problem

01:20:20.490 --> 01:20:20.990 align:middle line:90%
sets--

01:20:20.990 --> 01:20:21.840 align:middle line:90%
TA: Yes.

01:20:21.840 --> 01:20:24.690 align:middle line:90%
ERIK DEMAINE: --which was--

